<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Murdoch's Pearson stake slips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
News Corporation's stake in Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has now
dropped below 3 per cent, which is the lowest point for more than six years.
In February 1988 Mr Rupert Murdoch held a 20.5 per cent stake in the
publishing group, but reduced the cost of the holding by issuing Pounds 147m
worth of preference shares convertible into Pearson shares. The stake has
fallen ever since.
By November 1993 it was down to 4.9 per cent, and by February 21 the Murdoch
stake had fallen to 3.35 per cent.
The Stock Exchange was notified yesterday as the News Corp interest fell
below 3 per cent mainly, Pearson believes, through the continuing process of
conversion and redemption of shares.
</TEXT>
