<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Midland bounces back to Pounds 844m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Midland Bank, the UK high street banking arm of HSBC Holdings, quadrupled
pre-tax profits to Pounds 844m last year, against Pounds 204m in 1992 in
spite of weak demand for loans and a decline in fees and commissions
obtained through branches.
Operating profits before provisions for bad debts rose to Pounds 1.4bn,
against Pounds 795m, thanks to strong income from treasury and capital
markets trading.
Sir Brian Pearse, who is about to retire as chief executive, said the UK
retail bank 'continues to operate under very difficult and trying
circumstances in a market that is over-supplied'.
The bad debt charge against lending in the UK fell by Pounds 118m to Pounds
447m, but this was offset by a Pounds 37m charge for loans to less developed
countries, and a Pounds 50m general provision against future corporate
failures. The worst bad debt experience was in overseas commercial banking -
mainly France and Germany - where the charge rose by Pounds 108m to Pounds
131m.
Sir Brian said that complaints in the UK fell by 40 per cent last year after
efforts to consult customers. Adjustments to charges for personal customers
had included abolishing some fees.
First Direct, Midland's telephone banking subsidiary, increased its customer
base to more than 500,000 accounts by the end of the year. However, it only
achieved a trading profit in December. Sir Brian said that First Direct had
not achieved the same level of cross-selling financial products, such as
mortgages, as in the branches.
Midland paid a dividend of Pounds 403m to HSBC from net profits of Pounds
646m. Retained profit of Pounds 243m, against Pounds 102m, boosted the ratio
of core capital to assets weighted by risk to 6.5 per cent, against 5.7 per
cent.
The bank said that its Midland Personal Financial Services arm had
undertaken about 7,000 transfers of personal pensions. It had reviewed the
cases and made a 'precautionary provision' against possible compensation.
Total assets rose to Pounds 76bn, against Pounds 71bn, in spite of a fall in
loans and advances to Pounds 38.6bn, against Pounds 42.5bn. Holdings of debt
securities surged from Pounds 5.8bn to Pounds 13bn.
</TEXT>
