<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Firmer bonds lift European share prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, CONNER MIDDELMANN and MICHAEL MORGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A further recovery in bond markets led share prices higher across Europe
yesterday. Bonds consolidated in calmer trading but traders said long-term
investors remained sidelined and cash activity was thin.
German bond markets firmed after the Bundesbank called for variable-rate
securities repurchase agreements, a move seen as paving the way for lower
short-term interest rates.
Later, encouraging comments from a member of the US Federal Reserve gave US
Treasuries a lift, further supporting European bond markets.
Prices eased on late profit-taking in the German bund market, where traders
were reluctant to hold paper ahead of the release of M3 money supply growth
numbers for January and amid tension in the Balkans and Russia.
UK gilts, however, held most of their gains, with the Liffe March long gilt
futures contract closing at 113 7/16 , up  5/8 point on the day.
In the London equity market, the FT-SE 100 Index closed at the best of the
day, a gain of 46.9 bringing it to 3,328.1. The Footsie has now recovered
all but 12 points of the ground lost last Thursday. Other European equity
markets were also firmer.
Bond markets, Page 33; Currencies Page 35; World stocks, Page 41; London
stocks, Page 44
