<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Management: Data Protection dodgers face fines - In a
Nutshell
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies that have failed to register under the 1984 Data Protection Act
risk fines of at least Pounds 5,000.
While 182,000 organisations have registered, some 150,000 computer users
have yet to do so, according to the national audit office.
Under the act, any organisation that keeps details about living people on
computer - even just names and addresses - must register their use of the
information.
The Data Protection Register is to launch a campaign to encourage
compliance. Failure to register is a criminal offence and can lead to fines
of Pounds 5,000 in the lower courts and unlimited fines in higher courts.
Registrar's Information Service. Tel 0625 535777.
</TEXT>
