<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Hard times after death of king coal: The fate of NUM
officials 10 years after the great strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ten years ago today Mr George Hayes, the National Coal Board's area director
for South Yorkshire, announced the closure of Cortonwood colliery,
triggering one of the largest national strikes in British industrial
history: the 1984-85 miners' strike.
Since the strike, the number of miners has fallen from 196,000 to about
14,000 with political and industrial consequences which have been well
charted.
What has happened to the local officials of the National Union of
Mineworkers? Those men - usually articulate and self-confident - formed a
unique labour movement elite at the heart of the mining communities.
As the pits have closed it is those men who have had furthest to fall,
losing not only a well-paid job but social status. Many now struggle to earn
a living as security guards, school caretakers, or taxi drivers and look
back nostalgically on the days when they were, in effect, managing the
working lives of hundreds of people.
Few have changed their views about the strike. Mr Alan Cummings, 46, a
senior official at Easington colliery, County Durham, still feels there was
a political vendetta against the strike and remains bitter about the lack of
support from the rest of the labour movement. Others, such as Mr Carl
Browning, lodge secretary at Celynen South in south Wales, blame Mr Arthur
Scargill for mishandling the dispute. Mr Cummings' pit only closed last
year, since when he has been winding up union business and is only next
month set to join the dole queue. Looking back, he says: 'The fact is we
were thrashed. It wasn't just 10-0 it was 100-0.'
He does not expect to be able to exploit his considerable experience of
managing people or even to find a job on the Peterlee industrial estate.
Instead he is thinking of returning to college.
A fellow official at Easington, Mr John MacManey, has found a job doing
unskilled work in a local factory packing batteries. Hardest to take is the
close supervision. 'Down a mine you have to be able to trust people to get
on with the job, but in factories they treat you like a moron,' he says.
Mr Mick Appleyard, 50, former secretary at Sharlston colliery in West
Yorkshire, suffers from arthritis and lives a lonely life on disability
benefit, seeing old comrades from the Yorkshire NUM circuit rarely.
Another official from Sharlston, Mr John Swithenbank, like many former
miners works as a security guard on half the pay he got as a miner. He works
for the Reliance security company on 12-hour shifts - three on days, three
on nights, and then three days off.
Mr Jim Heel, former NUM treasurer at Celynen South, survives as a
small-business owner. His wife's hardware retail business has expanded since
the pit closed and they run three shops.
Mr Carl Browning, the Celynen South secretary, works as a caretaker in a
local school, and has taken a large drop in earnings. He has remained
politically involved, however, and sits as a magistrate.
Sometimes miners take their strong union traditions into their new jobs. Mr
Frank Clarke, former secretary at South Kirkby colliery, got a job at the
Morrison supermarket in Wakefield and blew new life into the local TGWU
general union branch. But it has not been easy for Mr Clarke. As an NUM
official he was on full-time union business. As a TGWU representative at
Morrison's he has to do union work in his spare time after a 50-hour week
for little more than Pounds 150.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
