<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Two-thirds back unitary councils
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Two-thirds of people questioned by MORI, the pollsters, for the Local
Government Commission approve in principle of a unitary system of local
government.
The findings were released yesterday by the Association of District
Councils, which claimed that the polls showed that people wanted 'change,
not the status quo'.
But support for removing a tier of government was strongest in areas such as
Bristol and Cleveland where new counties were set up in 1974. The poll did
not present local people with detailed proposals for possible unitary
councils, and showed that in most areas only half of residents identified
strongly with their district or county council.
