<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Mortgage lending by big banks falls 25% in month
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mortgage lending by leading British banks fell by more than a quarter in
January compared with the month before.
Gross loans were Pounds 1.01bn, down from Pounds 1.36bn, according to
yesterday's figures from the British Bankers' Association. This was the
seventh successive monthly fall since the Pounds 1.72bn gross figure of June
last year.
Seasonally adjusted figures for net lending also dropped, from Pounds 733m
in December to Pounds 588m in January.
Mortgage approvals also continued to fall - to 19,297 approvals with a value
of Pounds 914m, after December figures of 20,348 with a value of Pounds
968m.
Approvals are seen as an important indicator of the state of the mortgage
market, so the fall of slightly more than 5 per cent is less discouraging
for the banks than December's sharper drop, which was reflected in January's
lower mortgage lending figures.
Mr John Ecklin, BBA statistics director, said yesterday that he expected the
leading banks' share of the UK mortgage market in January to be about 33 per
cent, compared with more than 35 per cent during 1993. This suggests that
building societies have begun to regain some ground.
</TEXT>
