<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Curb on baby milk adverts attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manufacturers of formula milk for babies yesterday attacked government
proposals to ban consumer advertising of the product as a 'scandal' which
would result in tougher laws than for tobacco.
The government finishes consulting on the proposed rules at the end of this
week and plans to have regulations in place by June. Health officials want
to see an increase in breastfeeding, which is considered better for babies.
The changes also follow a European Union directive.
Manufacturers in the UK are allowed to advertise to the retail trade, health
professionals and mothers through promotional literature distributed by
health workers. The new rules would allow advertising to health
professionals only, and would be much stricter than the requirements of the
EU directive.
The Infant and Dietetic Foods Association, which represents the main baby
milk manufacturers including Wyeth, Cow &amp; Gate and Milupa, said the milks
were 'a perfectly legal food but they are attempting to impose more
restrictions on us than on tobacco'.
The Advertising Association, which represents advertisers, said yesterday
that the ban was 'illogical, inappropriate and unnecessary'.
</TEXT>
