<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / OFT to investigate warranties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Office of Fair Trading is to investigate the sale of extended warranties
by retailers, after allegations that consumers are paying too much.
The warranties provide protection on products - commonly electrical goods -
after one-year guarantees have expired. The OFT was asked to carry out
preliminary research into warranties sales in January by Mr Neil Hamilton,
corporate affairs minister.
Mr Hamilton's decision came in response to a written question from Labour's
consumer affairs spokesman Mr Nigel Griffiths, who claimed some retailers
were selling extended warranties for more than twice what manufacturers
charged.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, said yesterday that
his inquiries had revealed a 'wide range of prices for extended warranties
on the same goods coupled with a lack of information about the choice of
cover available to consumers'.
The OFT would be consulting retailers, manufacturers and consumer groups to
consider whether greater 'transparency' was needed in the market, and how to
attain it.
The investigation may have important implications for electrical retailers,
particularly the market leaders Dixons, which also owns the Currys chain,
and Comet, part of the Kingfisher group.
Sales of warranties are thought to account for less than 10 per cent of
Dixons' sales, but some analysts believe they account for a large part of
the group's operating profits.
About a third of customers take out extended warranties.
Mr Griffiths claims that the electrical retailers, by failing to tell their
customers that cheaper alternatives are available, are 'profiteering at
their customers' expense'.
Retailers claim their warranties cost more because they cover all parts and
labour, as well as accidental damage, while manufacturers' warranties often
cover only failure of parts.
Retailers can also exchange products immediately with new ones if they are
not repairable, or replace them with another manufacturer's product.
The Radio, Electrical and Television Retailers' Association said it believed
the majority of retailers' warranties offered 'good value for money'.
</TEXT>
