<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / The Personal Pensions Time Bomb: SIB to issue information on
perils of opting out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Securities and Investments Board will this month take action to ensure
that people considering buying a personal pension instead of remaining in
their employer's or former employer's occupational scheme are aware of the
pitfalls.
This follows the City watchdog's publication last December of a pilot study
which suggested widespread failure among sales agents to comply with
regulators' standards and raised public concern about the mis-selling of
personal pensions. SIB said in an interim statement yesterday on its
progress in handling pension transfers and opt-outs, that a full report on
ensuring high standards in future business would be published after it had
been considered by SIB's board in mid-March.
The focus of this month's report is likely to be on ensuring that sales
agents properly explain the possible pension sale to customers, and on
strengthening the monitoring and control arrangements in companies and among
regulators.
There will also be a fact-sheet or checklist, intended to advise people what
issues they should raise with sales agents when discussing pension
transfers. It is likely to emphasise that most people in an occupational
scheme run by their current employer should probably not leave.
SIB's statement came as Labour MPs seized on the report in yesterday's
Financial Times to question Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary,
about the costs to the taxpayer of the growth in personal pensions. Mr
Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, asked whether the FT
investigation did not reveal 'an atmosphere of scandal' surrounding the
industry.
Mr Lilley vigorously defended the development of the private pensions
market. He said: 'If we didn't have the opportunity for people to opt for
private pensions where their firm has occupational pensions, many of those
40 per cent who are making greater provision than if they had stayed in
Serps would not have done so.'
SIB used yesterday's announcement to set out the planned timetable for work
on pension transfers.
By the end of April the self-regulating organisations such as Lautro, for
the life insurance industry, and Fimbra, for independent financial advisers,
must tell their members which categories of pension transfers they should
reconsider as a priority. The categories might include people coming up to
retirement, or those who have transferred out of a scheme with index-linked
benefits.
By the end of July the regulators will publish guidelines for companies and
regulators on compensation for people who received poor advice. There will
be advice for individual investors about how to respond and, if necessary,
how to complain.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
