FT  01 MAR 94 / Backbench Euro-sceptics stoke Tory election fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The difficulties facing Conservative party leaders in producing a unifying
manifesto for the Euro-elections in June were further underlined by renewed
demands from backbench Euro-sceptics in the Commons yesterday.
In a debate on moves towards the enlargement of the European Union through
the inclusion of newly democratic states in central and eastern Europe, they
reiterated calls for the renegotiation of the Maastricht treaty.
Mr John Biffen, Conservative MP for Shropshire North and a former Cabinet
minister, maintained that enlargement of the EU must involve re-examination
of commitments to a single European currency, a central bank and economic
convergence of the member states.
Such questions, he said, were not merely being raised by the 'awkward squad'
on the Tory back benches.
Mr Biffen pressed for a clear statement from all the leaders of the European
Union on the prospects for enlargement in the context of re-negotiating
existing commitments.
Mr Bill Cash, Conservative MP for Stafford and the most persistent critic of
the Maastricht treaty, said it was 'perfectly apparent' that it was not
working.
He also suggested that the Treaty of Rome, on which the original European
Community was founded, needed to be renegotiated as well.
Mr Bernard Jenkin, Conservative MP for Colchester North, warned that orders
providing for association agreements with Bulgaria, the Czech and Slovak
republics and with Romania could lead to the period for phasing out tariffs
on 'sensitive' products continuing for as long as 10 years.
