FT  01 MAR 94 / Howard launches volunteers initiative
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, will today announce government proposals
to increase voluntary activity in the community.
The initiative will build on plans to establish a national network of
volunteers as outlined by Mr John Major, prime minister, in October. Mr
Howard will emphasise the need for the private, public and voluntary sectors
to work together.
Local organisations will be able to bid for grants to finance projects that
increase the use of volunteers under a new award scheme proposed by the
government. The first awards will be made later this year.
Voluntary-sector leaders are concerned that in addition to calling for
concerted action the government could do more to encourage the use of
voluntary workers in areas such as health and education, where it has direct
responsibility.
Today's announcement coincides with the restructuring of Action Resource
Centre, the charitable organisation that arranges the secondment of
employees with business skills to voluntary organisations. It is to be known
as Action: Employees in the Community and will operate in conjunction with
Business in the Community.
This week also sees the launch of the government-supported Community
Development Foundation's Streets Ahead initiative, a campaign aimed at
encouraging the corporate sector to recognise the value of developing
practical links with community-based organisations.
