<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / PLO wants US to lean on Jerusalem
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON and DAVID HOROVITZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TUNIS, JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Palestine Liberation Organisation is to send envoys to Washington to
discuss with the US its 'requirements' for resuming peace talks with Israel,
following last week's massacre of Palestinians in Hebron, senior PLO
officials said yesterday.
The PLO representatives would seek US pressure on Israel to take tougher
steps to protect Palestinians in the occupied territories than those
announced at the weekend by Israel's Premier Yitzhak Rabin. The PLO has
already rejected as 'inadequate' Mr Rabin's move to disarm a few of the most
extreme Jewish settlers.
In Israel, Mr Rabin appealed to the PLO and the Arab states who have
suspended their peace talks with Israel (Syria, Lebanon and Jordan) to
return to the negotiating table. If they did not, they would be handing
victory to the extremists. At the same time, he rejected Palestinian demands
for all 120,000 Jewish settlers in the occupied territories to be disarmed
and for some settlements to be dismantled.
The PLO was also calling for United Nations observers in the occupied
territories.
In Washington, the State Department said the US believed the Israelis and
Palestinians should continue to negotiate on the basis of the declaration of
principles they signed at the White House last September, rather than
setting out new conditions.
'The agenda is the declaration of principles and how it can be implemented
and the full range of issues associated with the declaration. That has been
the agenda and will likely remain the agenda and must remain the agenda for
them to move ahead in the process,' said Mr Michael McCurry, State
Department spokesman.
Although the separate bilateral talks between Israel and Jordan, Syria and
Lebanon broke off on Sunday, the US believes they will resume. State
Department officials said Mr Farouk Sharaa, Syrian foreign minister, had
assured Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, that the break in the
talks represented 'a pause, not a retreat'.
The PLO hopes last Friday's massacre will galvanise international, and
especially US, opinion behind its demands; it believes this offers the only
prospect of forcing further concessions from the Israelis.
</TEXT>
