<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Major and Clinton mend their fences: The British premier's
visit to Pittsburgh
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton last night offered British Prime Minister John Major
a lavish welcome to the US as the two leaders sought to reaffirm the
strength of the transatlantic alliance.
Greeting his guest in Pittsburgh, Mr Clinton deliberately put aside the
countries' recent differences over Bosnia and Northern Ireland. Instead, he
told a crowd of 3,000 that London and Washington were 'working in
partnership' around the world.
As Mr Major looked on with obvious satisfaction, the US president listed a
joint approach to the ending of the cold war and reform in Russia, a common
stance on the Gatt world trade talks and agreement now on the west's
approach to Bosnia as examples of the strength of the relationship.
Mr Clinton then went out of his way to praise the 'political courage and
vision' shown by the prime minister in trying to end the violence in
Northern Ireland. The president's remarks drew an equally warm response from
Mr Major, who emphasised the 'huge array of personal and business contacts
that bind the people of our nations'.
The Pittsburgh encounter - chosen because Mr Major's grandfather and father
had once lived there - followed intense talks between Mr Major and senior
administration and congressional figures on Bosnia, Russia and British
policy in Northern Ireland.
US officials said the two leaders' informal talks in a Pittsburgh restaurant
and during a visit to a new development on the site of an old industrial
complex in which Mr Major's grandfather might once have worked were a clear
signal that Washington still regarded Britain as a reliable ally.
Mr Major's aides, clearly anxious to show the special relationship was alive
and well, went to elaborate lengths to point up the generous amount of time
Mr Clinton had allocated to the visiting prime minister. Mr Major was due to
return to Washington late last night to stay with the Clintons at the White
House.
For his part Mr Major offered unequivocal support for the action of US
aircraft in Bosnia which shot down Serbian aircraft violating the United
Nations no-fly zone over the former Yugoslav province.
Praising the US for its efforts to broker a deal between the Bosnian Moslems
and Croatia, he said the search for a political settlement would go on in
parallel with efforts to extend the US's recent success in lifting the siege
of Sarajevo. Meanwhile, London and Washington would work jointly at the UN
to return Sarejevo to civilian administration.
Mr Major, who insisted that reports of a breach between the two governments
had been 'wildly overdone', also made it clear that he expected no real
dispute over Britain's approach to Northern Ireland.
British officials said Mr Major had won the support of both Mr Christopher
and Mr Gore for a policy of continuing to back Russian President Boris
Yeltsin despite the threat to his position caused by the release of the
leaders of last year's attempted coup.
</TEXT>
