<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / Fight to rescue EU enlargement talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Strenuous high-level efforts were being made early this morning to rescue
talks aimed at getting Finland, Sweden, Austria and Norway into the European
Union by next year.
Negotiators 'stopped the clock' and pressed on beyond the midnight deadline
for concluding the talks, amid clear signs that Austria and Norway were
unable to agree entry terms.
Mired in detail, the two sides were set to continue through the early hours
into today, and one EU neg-otiator warned: 'This is starting to go
backwards.'
The EU member states were faced with either settling early entry terms for
Sweden and Finland, or adjourning the negotiations for a few days before
reconvening - possibly even at a summit of heads of government.
Mr Klaus Kinkel, Germany's foreign minister, joined the negotiations
yesterday with a plea from Chancellor Helmut Kohl for flexibility on both
sides to get all four applicants into the Union. Enlargement, he said, was
much more important than arguing over a few thousand tonnes of Norwegian
fish, one of the main sticking points in the talks.
Oslo is resisting Spanish demands for access to Norwegian fishing waters, as
well as French-inspired attempts to restrict access for Norwegian fish to
the EU single market for four years.
In addition, disputes over agriculture subsidies, the newcomers'
contributions to the EU budget, and transit rights for EU lorries through
the Austrian Alps, have still to be settled.
Germany, the EU's main paymaster, also warned that enlargement was part of
the 1992 Edinburgh summit deal, which agreed the 1994-99 EU budget
resources, including a doubling of aid to poorer countries like Spain,
Portugal, Greece and Ireland.
EU diplomats disclosed that Mr Felipe Gonzalez, Spanish prime minister, has
written to Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany to spell out Madrid's bottom
line. Though Spain still insists Norway cannot be allowed a better deal on
fish than the limited agreement Spain and Portugal got when they joined in
1986, Mr Gonzalez made clear he will not countenance significant change to
the EU's weighted majority voting rules to accommodate the newcomers.
Spain and the UK want to keep existing voting rules to preserve their
ability to block EU measures. Currently, 23 votes out of 76 - normally
meaning two large and one small member states - can stop legislation in the
Council of Ministers. If all four applicants enter, the 16 would share 90
votes.
A majority of the 12 want to maintain the carefully nurtured existing
balance between big and small EU club members by requiring 27 votes to block
proposals. This issue alone may need to be resolved by a summit, some EU
diplomats predicted.
</TEXT>
