<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Company News (This Week): Return to the black after the dark
years - Philips
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
On Thursday, the long-suffering shareholders in Philips, the Dutch
electronics group, will find out whether they can expect to receive a
dividend this year - for the first time since the company fell into
difficulties in 1990 and embarked on its 'Centurion' restructuring programme
under its then new president, Mr Jan Timmer.
Analysts are divided on whether Philips will resume a pay-out with the 1993
results. An immediate resumption of the last dividend of Fl 2.00 per share,
paid out of 1989 profits, will not be possible, but there may be room for
around Fl 0.50.
There is certainly no doubt that Philips will be reporting a return to
profit. The company generated an exceptional gain of Fl 1.1bn (Dollars 570m)
on the sale of its 35 per cent stake in Matsushita Electronics Corp, a joint
venture with Matsushita of Japan. This will be more than enough to reverse
the previous year's net loss of Fl 900m.
Even without the help of extraordinary items, Philips is expected to post a
net profit of Fl 500m-Fl 850m. Much will depend on whether Christmas
shoppers stocked up on consumer electronics products to help the fortunes of
the company's single biggest business. Consumer electronics is expected to
have remained loss-making in 1993, but Philips has said it hopes to reach
break-even this year.
Another big question is how many consumers have been tempted to buy the
company's two latest mass market products, the digital compact cassette
(DCC), which is designed to replace the analogue cassette and to compete
with Sony's Mini Disc system, and compact disc-interactive, a multi-media
version of the popular CD player.
Philips will be aided by the robust results expected from PolyGram, its 75
per cent-owned music and film company, reporting in London today.
</TEXT>
