<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Survey of Jamaica (5): System seems short on credibility - A
look at a political scene ripe for revision and reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The ties that have bound Jamaicans to their political parties over half a
century are loosening and the bitter ideological debates that divided the
parties are now past. What is left is a battle for the new floating voters,
and a widespread sense that Jamaica's political system and its politicians
have not served it well.
While the antipathy towards politics is not unique to Jamaica, it is
recognised even by politicians themselves and has driven forward a proposed
revision of the country's 1962 constitution.
'The way parliament is structured and the system of voting together mean
that our system lacks credibility completely,' says Mr Edward Seaga of the
opposition Jamaica Labour Party (JLP).
The collapse of the socialist economies has been followed in Jamaica by a
migration by the governing People's National Party (PNP) across the
ideological spectrum - a shift led by Mr Michael Manley, who as prime
minister in the 1970s tried to move the country towards socialism.
After winning power in 1989, Mr Manley handed over power to his successor,
Mr Percival Patterson, who himself won a landslide victory against the JLP
last March. The PNP took 52 of the 60 seats in Jamaica's lower house, the
margin of victory exaggerated by the Westminster style first-past-the-post
voting system.
In the election, some 11 people were killed in the political violence that
has marred Jamaican elections for 30 years or more. In the worst year of
election violence, 1980, some 800 people were killed as rival party
supporters battled each other.
Many voters' entrenched positions have softened over the years as a result
of social and economic changes. In one sense, government has become less
important. Deregulation and liberalisation have reduced the government's
role in the economy. Budget stringency has meant that the powers of
political patronage which tied many voters to parties have weakened.
Mr Brian Meeks, lecturer in government at the University of the West Indies,
says that other factors include the weakening of the family, through which
party loyalty was traditionally passed. The growth of remittances from
Jamaicans living abroad has reduced the importance of the local economy to
some voters. To others living in some areas of the capital, loyalty to a
politician has been replaced by loyalties to a local gang leader or Don.
'Politicians can't afford to finance criminals . . . Criminal elements are
now linked to drugs and no longer hold on to the coat-tails of politicians,'
says Mr Bruce Golding, chairman of the JLP. The prime minister says: 'The
analysis of the available evidence establishes clearly that politics is a
decreasing factor in the present level of crime and violence.'
However, the perception that some politicians and criminals are closely
linked - or were linked in the past - has led to questions about whether the
political will exists to tackle the issue.
Crime is not the only concern of voters, who have seen successive
governments fail to raise living standards beyond the levels of 15 years ago
and who are frightened by inflation.
The constitutional revision is part of an effort to reassure voters that
things can work better, although it is far from clear that the electorate is
engaged in what some see as an arcane debate among politicians.
The Jamaican system is even more centralised than the Westminster system on
which is was modelled. The prospect of a revolt by the government's
backbenchers' revolt is so remote there is no need for party whips -
although a rebellion in the opposition JLP tried to unseat Mr Seaga as its
leader. The prime minister has enormous power of patronage (far exceeding
his counterpart in London).
There are therefore few, if any, effective checks and balances on the power
of the prime minister. 'There is absolutely no gridlock in our system. We
have a smooth highway that leads straight to an authoritarian prime
minister. We need a bit more gridlock,' says Mr Meeks of the University of
the West Indies. Nonetheless, Mr Golding is among a number of politicians
who believe that fear of a legislative gridlock will leave the system still
modelled on Westminster even after the constitution is revised.
A revision will probably establish a charter of rights for citizens. Among
likely changes is the appointment of an advocate general who will seek to
uphold citizens' rights against the government, on the assumption that the
current position of attorney general is too beholden to the government of
the day.
It may also change the size and composition of the Senate. The Upper House
is currently appointed: 13 members by the governing party; eight by the
leader of the opposition - a split meant to ensure that the two-thirds
majority needed for important constitutional changes requires a measure of
cross-party support. The most likely change will enlarge the Senate to 31
members and provide for it to be directly elected through proportional
representation.
Some provisions - such as the replacement of the Queen as head of state -
must be backed by a referendum, as well as a two-thirds majority of both
houses.
Mr Patterson says that constitutional change would not have to be voted upon
in one block. A joint committee of both houses will first have to decide on
what changes should be proposed: it could issue a set of interim proposals
before the final recommendation are issued.
Some provisions would only require a simple majority in parliament to be
changed, while others - so-called entrenched provisions - require a bill to
be laid before the house for six months before votes requiring two-thirds
majorities in both houses. The so-called deeply entrenched provisions -
which includes changing the head of state - would additionally require a
referendum.
Getting agreement between the two parties on constitutional reform is
complicated by a controversy over election procedures. The government has
promised there will be no further national elections until the electoral
system - including a clean up of electoral lists and better checks on double
voting - is improved. Local government elections due last year have already
been postponed and may have to be put back further.
However, the JLP says it wants such changes in place before by-elections are
held and is boycotting elections until changes are made. As an illustration
of some of the problems, in the last by-election - for a seat vacated to
allow the new finance minister Mr Omar Davies to take up his cabinet
position - 99.8 per cent of votes counted were cast for the ruling party. At
some polling stations, the vote for the PNP was over 100 per cent.
Whatever happens, when the next election comes around - it can be held as
late as March 1997 but is more likely to be in 1995 or 1996 - Mr Seaga is
likely to be competing as leader of the opposition.
He says the struggle for the leadership of the party by the so-called Gang
of Five did hurt the JLP, but has 'now purged' the system. Asked if it will
be he who leads the party to the next election, he said: 'It looks like it.'
Observers of the Jamaican political scene believe Mr Seaga has his eye on
history. Like his rival Michael Manley, he would like to bow out of a long
political career as prime minister, bequeathing leadership of the party and
government to an anointed successor, probably Mr Golding.
</TEXT>
<XX>
