<PROFILE>_AN-EB1DPAEIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Survey of Jamaica (4): Monetary brakes applied - Finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government deregulation has changed the shape of Jamaica's financial system,
and made it a growing sector of an overall sluggish economy.
Rapid inflation has reinforced the trend. But the shift last year to high
real interest rates has been making the environment tougher for many
financial institutions.
Even before the government applied the monetary brakes, slow growth in the
economy as a whole was taking its toll and competition was intensifying. The
financial sector grew only 4.2 per cent in 1992, the last year for which
figures are available, after double digit growth every year since 1987.
Financial services grew because of liberalisation of the Jamaican economy,
which started as long ago as 1986. Growth in the early years was
spectacular. 'Now that the market is becoming less protected and more
competitive, margins are narrowing,' says Mr Delroy Lindsay, chairman and
chief executive of the Corporate Group, a financial holding company.
For banks, in particular, times have got tougher. Mr Charles Ross, executive
director of Private Sector Organisation of Jamaica, says: 'High interest
rates have put the financial system under a fair amount of strain. Banks
have been accustomed to a fairly accommodating stance from the Bank of
Jamaica. Now with penal interest rates on overdrafts at the Bank of Jamaica
 -on overdrafts for over three days, rates are 120 per cent - they have to
manage their liquidity very closely.'
Mr Jacques Bussieres, the Canadian governor of the central bank, says the
Bank of Jamaica has been slightly more accommodating since the new year, but
with nominal interest rates still above 50 per cent, there is little real
evidence that pressure is easing.
Bankers admit that high interest rates put pressure on some of their
borrowers, but there is no sense that any bank is in trouble. The Bank of
Jamaica's powers of regulation and supervision were substantially increased
under a law passed in December 1992.
Banks have been helped by the very generous margins which have provided a
cushion for these harder times. They have also been assisted, says Mr Paul
Chen-Young, executive chairman of the Eagle Merchant Bank group of 16
companies, by those savers slow in moving their funds out of low-yielding
savings accounts. Banks are paying 15-18 per cent on savings deposits with
inflation at 30 per cent and treasury bills at 50-52 per cent. There is some
JDollars 17bn in such savings accounts, which, in effect, means a transfer
of resources to banks from individual savers of about JDollars 2.5bn a year.
But there is a widespread view that further mergers in the banking system
are likely.
The merger of the largest bank, National Commercial, and the third largest,
Mutual Security, may have set this trend under way. 'Eleven commercial banks
and 40 merchant banks seems a bit excessive for a country with 2.5m people,'
says Mr Lindsay. Nonetheless, the large Jamaican population overseas, which
remits home (it is estimated) anywhere between Dollars 250m and Dollars 400m
a year, may help sustain a larger financial system than would otherwise be
warranted.
Overseas and foreign currency business is becoming an increasingly important
part of the business of Jamaican financial services companies. Since the
liberalisation of the foreign exchange laws, funds held in foreign currency
accounts in Jamaican banks have grown to USDollars 500m. Many of these
accounts - paying interest rates of 6 to 8 per cent - are held by Jamaicans
resident in the US. There are, says Mr Chen-Young, 'a lot of Miami
addresses' on these accounts.
Having access to dollars allows the banks to provide trade finance without
having to obtain lines of credit from overseas, and permits direct lending
to exporters in dollars. The banks have had to place 25 per cent (now coming
down to 22 per cent) of these funds on deposit with the central bank, a
factor which has helped the country's net international reserves to turn
positive for the first time in years.
To encourage longer term flows, the central bank has decided that foreign
currency deposits of longer than 366 days will not attract reserves
requirements.
The moves overseas by financial groups have been helped by an improving
perception of Jamaican risk in the international financial market.
Whereas Jamaican commercial bank debt traded around 35 per cent of face
value in 1987, it now trades at over 80 per cent in the secondary market.
A commercial paper market is growing which, if it continues, will tend to
deprive banks of some better quality borrowers. A housing finance market is
in place, although high interest rates obviously deter borrowers. The
insurance business is growing, although stagnation in the economy has meant
that the pension fund business has been slow.
Yet while mechanisms are in place to provide long term finance in local
currency and to underwrite share issues, it will not do so again until
inflation falls substantially - along with interest rates.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JMZ  Jamaica, Caribbean.
</CN>
