<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Equity Markets: Other Markets
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANKFURT
The Bundesbank is unlikely to add to last week's uncertainty by opting for a
variable rate at Wednesday's repo operation, says NatWest Securities. With
the IG Metall ballot in Lower Saxony likely to show strong support for a
strike, the bond market is likely to be most reassured by a fixed rate repo
10 - 20 basis points below the current 6 per cent. This would be enough to
show that European rates are still free to move downwards, but not so much
as to arouse fears that the Bundesbank, whose council meets on Thursday, is
losing its grip.
AMSTERDAM
The results season gets under way in earnest this week. Polygram reports
today with UBS expecting a 20.3 per cent increase in net profits on 10.5 per
cent higher sales. Bols Wessanen is forecast to report a 5 per cent rise in
net profits on Wednesday and Philips is seen posting a Fl 805m net profit on
Thursday, after 1992's Fl 900m loss.
ZURICH
Credit Suisse and Swiss Volksbank present full-year consolidated results
together for the first time on Friday. The figures will represent about 70
per cent of the total CS Holding result.
PARIS
Chargeurs, the textile and communications group, which has undergone a major
restructuring during the last year, is expected to post a net loss of FFr200
on Thursday, down from a profit of FFr366m in 1992.
MILAN
The privatisation of Banca Commerciale Italiana begins today and is
scheduled to conclude on Friday. The offer could, however, close early if,
as was the case in the recent IMI sell-off, it is heavily oversubscribed.
TOKYO
Domestic investors will continue to take a cautious stance as companies take
profits on their investment portfolios before the March-end book-closing.
Although some economists expect tomorrow's tankan, the Bank of Japan's
quarterly report on business sentiment, to indicate a bottoming out of the
economy, domestic institutions, unlike overseas investors, are unlikely to
accumulate positions ahead of the fiscal year-end.
