<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Equity Markets: Shares still attuned to bond trends - New
York
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Equity investors are entering a potential minefield this week, with a batch
of signals on inflation laid out before them and fears over the direction of
monetary policy running rampant.
'We're not going to have a lot of fun,' says Mr Alfred Goldman, technical
analyst at AG Edwards &amp; Sons, a St Louis securities house. 'We just had the
first truly nasty week of a correction. The market is going to lose sleep
over the weekend thinking about it, and the bears will be licking out their
chops on Monday morning.'
As last week's action demonstrated, shares are still closely attuned to bond
market trends. The results were not pretty. The Treasury market went into a
mid-week tail-spin, haunted by real and imagined signs that the Federal
Reserve was poised for a second strike on interest rates, three weeks after
the first.
Shares followed bonds down, ignoring the completion of a fourth-quarter
reporting season that brought news of a 60 per cent gain in corporate
earnings and solid evidence of continued growth in the current three-month
period.
By the week's end, the Dow Jones Industrial Average showed a 47-point net
decline to 3,838.78, including Thursday's 51-point rout, triggered by the
collapse of Bell Atlantic's proposed merger with Tele-Communications Inc.
Mr Goldman believes the market will suffer more losses this week, no matter
how the bond market performs. 'In a correction, bad news is bad, and good
news is bad, too,' he says.
Mr Peter Cardillo, director of research at Westfalia Investments in New
York, agrees that Wall Street will probably have to navigate some choppy
activity over the next five days. But he sees shares continuing to 'feed
off' the bond market and links a further slide in prices this week to
developments there.
'Investors are spooked by high interest rates,' he says, adding that the
anxiety is likely to abate in the next few weeks. Reassurance will depend on
more data suggesting the economy is no danger of overheating, beginning with
Tuesday's purchasing managers' index, a good leading indicator of the
economy's pace.
The week will culminate with Friday's report on the February employment
trends. Analysts are looking for an increase of 150,000 in payrolls last
month. If their estimates prove accurate, Mr Cardillo believes shares could
return to stability, although February's cold weather may provide an excuse
to explain away a favourable reading.
If the forecast proves to have been timid, however, a big sell-off is
possible.
On a bright note, bargain hunters are expected to give a lift to
telecommunications and cable stocks, which were battered last week when Bell
Atlantic's announcement raised an unexpected detour in the development of
the 'information superhighway'. The sector's rebound was already evident on
Friday, when the technology-rich Nasdaq composite index clearly outperformed
the large-cap indices.
</TEXT>
<XX>
