<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / World Bond Markets: Frankfurt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was a lugubrious week for German government securities and the mood of
the market is unlikely to improve in the days ahead.
The steep rise in yields was driven by knock-on effects of the US Federal
Reserve's small rate increase in early February. It has helped foreign
investors, massive buyers of bunds last year, to revise their view of the
attractions of the German market.
Even if the trend of German interest rates is down, in contrast to the
probability of steadily rising rates in the US, the prospect of further
Bundesbank rate cuts is not enough to inspire foreign investors to buy
heavily into the bund market, says Klaus Holschuh, head of fixed income
research at Commerzbank.
On the contrary, foreign investors will be looking to seize on any data they
can interpret as an excuse to sell. The Bundesbank will duly oblige by
publishing the January M3 supply figure today or tomorrow. Following on from
the distorted December figure - the annualised, seasonally adjusted growth
in M3 was 8.1 for that month - further distortions are likely to take the
January growth figure to 10 per cent or more.
No matter that the figure is genuinely distorted, and that underlying
inflation is well on the way down, the data is likely to be seen as a good
reason for selling bunds.
</TEXT>
