<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / World Bond Markets: New York
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If there was any doubt left in anyone's mind, last week confirmed that the
long bull run in bonds had reached a turning point. Mr Alan Greenspan,
chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, may have talked tough on inflation in
his testimony to Congress on Tuesday, but bond prices kept sinking. The
yield on 30-year Treasury bonds has risen nearly half a point since the Fed
raised short-term rates on February 4.
This week, a mass of economic data will provide the market with the
opportunity to feed on its own fears. Revised figures for gross domestic
product in last year's fourth quarter are due today, with some economists
predicting that the earlier estimate of 5.9 per cent could translate into an
actual 7 per cent. The purchasing managers' index of buying intentions is on
Tuesday, followed by personal income and home sales figures on Wednesday,
factory stocks on Thursday, then employment indicators on Friday.
In one sense, it hardly matters what the numbers say. If the figures point
to rapid economic growth, bond prices will fall. If the numbers are weak,
people will say it was a weather-related aberration, and prices will still
fall. That is the sort of mood the market is in. It is convinced the last
interest rate rise was only the first of many - and that the next is not far
away.
</TEXT>
