<DATE>940228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / World Bond Markets: ECP sector gaining in popularity -
International
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Although it has been overshadowed by the bigger and more glamorous Eurobond
market over the past few years, the European commercial paper (ECP) market
has been enjoying a quiet but steady rise in its popularity.
Renewed confidence in the market's ability to provide quick access to
short-term liquidity at competitive rates is seen as the main factor helping
to attract a growing number of issuers and investors.
BZW said in a recent review that question marks over the liquidity and
efficiency of the ECP market were finally eliminated last June when the
Kingdom of Denmark raised as much as Dollars 1.5bn in a matter of days to
support the Danish krone when it came under attack from foreign exchange
speculators.
Confidence in the market's depth was given a further boost by the launch of
large ECP programmes by Ford Credit Europe, Hanson and Guinness which
allowed them to quickly raise funds of more than Dollars 1bn, amounts which
have previously been the sole domain of sovereign borrowers.
Mr David Knight, managing director of CP operations at BZW, says the
progressive convergence of rates between the domestic CP market in the US,
where outstandings are estimated at Dollars 500bn, and the ECP market has
meant that at times, rates in the ECP market are lower than in the US.
'This has resulted in cheaper cost of funding for US companies,' he says,
adding that the ECP market also provides them with a tax-efficient way of
funding their European operations.
Mr Chris van Niekerk, director of money-market business at Swiss Bank Corp
in London, also attributes the rise in ECP volume to the inroads which the
ECP market has made into the German and Swiss domestic markets as a result
of deregulation in the two countries. Issuers can now issue in D-Marks and
Swiss francs directly under their ECP programmes. 'Calling it a Euro-CP
market is a bit of a misnomer because it is becoming a global CP market
outside the US domestic market,' he says.
The short maturities available in the ECP market, from one day to 364 days,
make ECP highly suitable as an underlying asset for investors wishing to
swap into other currencies which have greater yields. Mr van Niekerk
estimates that 35 per cent of the ECP volume issued by borrowers in dollars
is swapped into other currencies by investors. 'Due to the volatility in the
currency market this has been a fruitful activity for investors,' he says.
The revival in the market's fortunes has been reflected in an increase in
dollar-denominated ECP issuance, which accounts for around 80 per cent of
the whole ECP market. Having dropped as low as Dollars 75.1bn last March,
dollar-denominated ECP outstandings rose as high as Dollars 85.1bn in
November. They are currently estimated to be about Dollars 81.5bn.
Ms Julie Joe, CP product manager at Lehman Brothers, is optimistic on
prospects for 1994 and believes ECP market volume could increase by 10-15
per cent this year. 'The bearish interest-rate environment favours issuance
in the short-term market,' she says.
In recent years, the downward spiral in interest rates has prompted issuers
to lock in historically low rates with long-dated bond issues. However, this
type of financing has become more difficult since the start of this year as
the fear of higher interest rates has prompted investors to focus on the
short end of the yield curve.
Lesser dependence on time deposits by clearing banks has also encouraged
investors to park liquid assets in the ECP market, where rates are often
more favourable. At the same time, the short-term nature of the ECP market
meets the investment criteria of Far Eastern investors who are increasingly
flush with cash.
ECP experts believe that as a greater fluidity develops between the ECP
market and US CP market, investors who buy ECP will become more flexible
regarding the credit ratings of issuers.
At present, investors in ECP tend to be rather conservative and restrict
themselves to paper issued by top-rated borrowers. However, as in other
fixed-income and equity markets, there has been growing investor demand for
unrated ECP issued by emerging market borrowers, notably from Mexico.
As a result of this 'black-and-white' attitude to credit ratings, many
issuers with mediocre ratings have difficulty in raising significant sums in
the ECP market. By contrast, they have relatively good access to the US
domestic market.
Mr Knight believes that the improving economic climate in the US and the UK
(these two geographic regions account for 33 per cent of all ECP issues)
should see an improvement in the fortunes of borrowers which have been
downgraded over the past few years. 'The upgrading to the critical A1/P1
level will allow heavy issuers to resume issuance,' he says.
In addition to the ECP market accepting a wider range of credits, Ms Joe
highlights the asset-backed sector as a potential area for growth. This kind
of issuance is already well-developed in the US.
</TEXT>
<XX>
