<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / World Bond Markets: London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Traders will be hoping that the gilts market can enjoy a respite this week
after the battering it has taken since the start of the year. The benchmark
9 per cent 2008 issue has fallen by around nine points since January 1,
while the yield has risen from 6.38 to 7.23 per cent.
Many feel the falls in prices have ignored the promising economic outlook.
'Nothing has changed in the past few weeks to justify a change in the
fundamental view of inflation in the UK,' say Mr Julian Wiseman and Mr David
Mackie of J P Morgan.
There are few economic statistics due this week which could change the mood
of the UK market. The main event will be Wednesday's monthly monetary
meeting between Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor of the exchequer, and Mr Eddie
George, governor of the Bank of England.
After the poor reaction to last month's rate cut, the duo could be forgiven
for being cautious about further cuts; on the other hand, the April tax
increases have yet to hit consumers' pockets.
Any decision to cut rates would not be acted upon immediately, giving the
market plenty of scope for speculation, but it is hard to resist the
conclusion that it will be the mood of international bond markets, and
particularly US Treasuries, that will determine the short-term fate of
gilts.
</TEXT>
