<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Currency Markets: Focus on US labour market statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Foreign exchange markets this week will watch closely the release on Friday
of February labour market data for an indicator of the likely course of US
monetary policy.
It was the tightening of policy earlier this month, after the release of the
January labour data, which threw international financial markets into
disarray, from which they have yet to emerge.
The Humphrey-Hawkins testimony last week of Mr Alan Greenspan, chairman of
the US Fed, signally failed to quell market fears about resurgent US
inflation.
Friday's data will offer a concrete basis to either confirm or confound
market pessimism about US inflation prospects.
The logical beneficiary of fears about higher US interest rates should be
the dollar. Last week, though, the US currency was generally weaker as fears
of a stronger yen dragged it down against other currencies.
In Europe, attention will revert to Germany. Today the Bundesbank will
announce the terms of its weekly repo, while the policy-making council meets
on Thursday.
Commentators believe the US may well have used the weekend meeting of G7
finance ministers in Frankfurt to urge the case for lower German interest
rates.
Although the Bundesbank cut its discount rate by 50 basis points at the last
council meeting, it did not lower the repo rate - the main instrument for
influencing money market rates. There is speculation that the central bank
may this week announce a variable rate repo. This would indicate a
willingness to see lower rates.
These factors might be outweighed by the unresolved labour dispute in the
engineering industry, and rumours that the January M3 number could be as
high as 13 per cent. There are also indications that the Bundesbank is more
concerned with steadying market expectations than outright monetary easing.
Weakness last week in the bund market can only have encouraged further
caution.
In the UK attention will be focused on Wednesday's monthly monetary policy
meeting between Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie George,
governor of the Bank of England. Their last meeting resulted in a
quarter-point cut in rates.
Subsequent economic data has left a definite impression that the UK economic
recovery is weaker than previously thought. Commentators also believe that
an easing of monetary policy is likely ahead of the fiscal tightening in
April when new tax increases come into effect.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
