<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / International Company News: BBV declares interest in gaining
control of Banesto
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Banco Bilbao Vizcaya has become the third big Spanish bank to publicly
declare its interest in controlling Banesto, the ailing financial
institution.
Banesto is to be recapitalised by the domestic banking sector and then
auctioned, either to a single domestic bank or a pool of banks.
Mr Emilio Ybarra, BBV chairman, told shareholders at the weekend 'we could
go (to the auction) alone, in association with one or more financial
institutions or we could even not go at all if we do not believe the
conditions (of the auction) to be acceptable.'
Rival banks, Banco Santander and Argentaria, the partially privatised state
banking corporation, have hired SG Warburg, the UK merchant bank, and
Goldman Sachs of the US respectively, to help them prepare bids for Banesto.
Mr Ybarra said Merrill Lynch, the US investment bank, will advise BBV.
The winner of the auction will take over a large branch network, making it
the leader of the domestic banking sector and one of the major financial
institutions in Europe.
It will, however, be burdened by Banesto's mounting losses and by the badly
damaged quality of its assets.
The critical state of Banesto's balance sheet prompted the authorities to
dismiss the bank's directors at the end of last year and to put a caretaker
board in charge.
Mr Ybarra said he believed Banesto would post a 1993 net loss of more than
Pta50bn.
Before the auction, the domestic institutions and the Bank of Spain will
absorb bad debts valued at Pta285bn and inject Pta180bn of fresh capital in
the form of a share issue.
If the rescue plan is approved by Banesto shareholders at the annual meeting
on March 26, the Bank of Spain will seek to have bids delivered by April 12.
</TEXT>
