<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Scottish Power in talks over Clydesdale
deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Scottish Power is negotiating to extend its network of retail stores into
England by buying part of the Clydesdale Group, the Glasgow-based electrical
retailer which went into receivership last month.
It is thought to be interested primarily in Clydesdale's 30 out-of-town
superstores south of the border.
However, the deal is believed to include the 12 superstores in Scotland,
where Scottish Power already has about 30 per cent of the white goods
market, as well as the group's rental business.
Scottish Power's offer has led to the abandonment of a Pounds 46m bid for
the entire group from Clydesdale managers.
This group is not interested in buying Clydesdale's high street shops
without its Scottish superstores and the rental operation. But it hopes
Scottish Power may be forced by the Office of Fair Trading to shed the
Scottish superstores as soon as a deal is concluded, which might enable it
to revive the bid.
</TEXT>
