<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Independent likely to favour all-cash MGN bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The battle for The Independent newspaper is expected to enter its final
phase either today or tomorrow with the likelihood that an improved bid by
the consortium which includes Mirror Group Newspapers will be recommended by
the board.
The improved deal, being worked on by lawyers last night, would add a full
cash alternative to match or come close to MGN's existing Pounds 3.50 offer
in cash and shares.
Mr Ian Hay Davison, chairman of Newspaper Publishing, the company that owns
both The Independent and the Independent on Sunday, has been determined that
all institutional shareholders should have an equal chance of getting out of
the company.
Although Mr Tony O'Reilly, chairman of Independent Newspapers of Ireland,
offered Pounds 3.50 in cash for his initial 24.9 per cent stake, last week's
offer from the MGN consortium still only had a cash alternative of Pounds
2.50.
If the MGN consortium comes up with a full cash alternative, the
non-executive directors of Newspaper Publishing will recommend the offer.
The other members of the consortium are El Pais of Spain, La Repubblica of
Italy and the founders of The Independent, led by Mr Andreas Whittam Smith
Lawyers were also working last night on the precise form of guarantees of
editorial independence. MGN has already said it will not vote on hiring or
firing of editors and will allow the Spanish and Italian newspaper groups
together to have a voting majority in the company.
Under the plan now emerging, the stake of the founders would come down from
10 per cent to 3 per cent. The shares would be sold to MGN making it the
second-largest shareholder with 27 per cent. El Pais and La Repubblica would
each have 20 per cent.
Even if the bid is recommended, Mr O'Reilly who now controls 29.9 per cent
of the company could return with a higher bid but he has always said it was
unlikely he would mount a full takeover.
</TEXT>
