<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / G7 warns embattled Yeltsin to maintain reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON, QUENTIN PEEL and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, KRONBERG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Russia's rulers floundered in angry embarrassment yesterday as the freed
leaders of last October's bloody parliamentary uprising taunted the
president who thought he had put them in jail for years.
Under severe political pressure following the release of his enemies,
President Boris Yeltsin was also given a blunt warning by his western allies
at the weekend to maintain the pace of economic reform in Russia despite the
recent departure of leading reformers from government.
The Group of Seven industrialised states, meeting near Frankfurt at the
weekend, warned Moscow it must reach agreement with the International
Monetary Fund on stabilising inflation and the government deficit before any
further debt rescheduling could be negotiated.
In Moscow, Mr Vyacheslav Kostikov, Mr Yeltsin's press spokesman, described
the decision to free the leaders of the October uprising as 'sacrilege' and
the parliament which made it as 'an accomplice in lawlessness'.
Mr Kostikov, who is prone to make threats exceeding the Russian leader's
appetite for action, said Mr Yeltsin 'reserved the right to act in
accordance with the constitutional powers he is entrusted with' - a possible
reference to his right to impose a state of emergency in situations of
national danger.
Mr Alexander Rutskoi, the former vice-president, who came out of jail
wearing his full general's uniform despite the fact that he was stripped of
his rank for leading the uprising, has given himself two weeks to decide
whether he plans to run for president in 1996.
The tough G7 line on insisting that Russia agree with the IMF before any new
round of official debt rescheduling in the Paris Club emerged from
Saturday's meeting between the G7 finance ministers and central bank
governors, and a Russian delegation headed by Mr Sergei Dubinin, the acting
finance minister.
It will put the new Russian government under pressure to reach a deal with
the IMF on the conditions for the release of a second Dollars 1.5bn (Pounds
1bn) tranche of its special transformation facility and a Dollars 4.1bn
stand-by credit.
Philip Stephens adds: Arriving in Washington early this morning, Mr John
Major, the prime minister, emphasised that the west must continue to support
Mr Yeltsin. In talks today with President Bill Clinton, he will urge
Washington to speed plans to offer Mr Yeltsin a stronger partnership with
Nato and a formal role in G7 summits.
G7 ties Russian debt to IMF accord, Page 2
