<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Accountancy firms 'should be monitored by single watchdog'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK's three regulatory bodies for auditors should be merged and subject
to independent public scrutiny, according to a confidential report
commissioned by the government.
The report says the current system for monitoring accountancy firms will do
little to improve the practices of the larger firms.
The draft report, which was submitted to the Department of Trade and
Industry late last month, was written by Mr Peter Moizer, professor of
accounting at the University of Leeds.
Ministers commissioned the report to assess the effectiveness of the first
two years of the system of self-regulation which was established by law in
1989.
The regulation of the profession's standards is split between three bodies.
The Joint Monitoring Unit examines the work of all the larger accounting
firms, which audit nearly all public limited companies. The unit is
controlled by the UK's three institutes of chartered accountants.
The other regulators are the Chartered Association of Certified Accountants
and the Association of Authorised Public Accountants.
The report says ideally there should be only one body to regulate the
professsion as the split between the regulators, which act as commercial
rivals, is inappropriate, wasteful and not the best way to improve the
quality of auditing. It calls for the creation of a body similar to the
Public Oversight Board which has operated in the US since 1977, which would
deal with customer complaints and produce an annual review of the
regulator's work.
The report says that short of radical reform, the Joint Monitoring Unit run
by the institutes of chartered accountants should follow the approach of the
other regulatory bodies, which are more effective.
The Moizer study says the unit spends more time on each visit to auditors
than the certified accountants' regulators, costs more, is less flexible and
is seen as more threatening by the firms being examined.
It recommends the unit should increase the number of annual visits so that
it matchs the other regulators by inspecting all firms in its jurisdiction
within the next five years, and then target those which are likely to be
higher risk.
Under the existing procedures, the unit examines a sample of firms each year
to draw general lessons which it can use to educate others.
At the current pace, it would take 50 years for all accountancy firms to be
visited.
The report also recommends that there is an urgent need for an authoritative
statement on how auditors should deal with problems peculiar to small
companies.
See Lex
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8721 Accounting, Auditing, and Bookkeeping Services.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
    TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
</TP>
