<PROFILE>_AN-EB1DPACVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / The Lex Column: Accountancy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Debate about the liability of accountants for the errors of their ways seems
to be hotting up again. Claims against accountancy firms are rising, yet the
alarm felt by the profession may not play to a wider audience. Indeed,
rather the reverse. Ever since the Law Lords handed largesse to the
accountants by deciding that auditors were not accountable to individual
shareholders, a backlash has been in prospect. A nebulous duty to
shareholders as a group is all but useless, since they cannot sue
collectively. Shareholders want a better grip on auditors.
The profession's case is not helped by the fact that poor audits and
negligence have been widespread. Large firms have driven for market share in
audits in the hope that they can gain clients for other services. That
competition has put pressure on audit fees. In some cases audits have become
loss-leaders, and the temptation has been to maintain margins by using
inexpensive trainees. Mistakes have become more likely.
The contention that one of the big partnerships may be broken by these
rising claims is impossible to test, since none reveal their financial
position in any detail. Accountants may want to cap their liabilities or
restrict them to the elements for which they are directly responsible. For
that the very least they will have to cede is a concrete duty to
shareholders and greater openness about their financial affairs.
</TEXT>
