<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / The Lex Column: Food manufacturers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Unilever's Pounds 490m restructuring charge throws up further worries about
UK food manufacturers as they steady their nerves to report results. If one
of the world's strongest consumer products companies continues to apply the
squeeze to costs it would be fair to assume that its lesser rivals will have
to follow. The fear is that such exceptional restructuring charges may
become a permanent feature of the sector - which raises the question whether
they should be regarded as exceptional at all. In the squeaky new world of
FRS3 accounting, it makes little difference given such charges have to be
taken above the line. But it provides another reason for believing the
sector's earnings are likely to remain dull for the foreseeable future.
That said, many UK food manufacturers rationalised capacity savagely
throughout the 1980s as retailers applied the cosh. Moreover, much of
Unilever's charge relates to the US detergents market where Procter &amp; Gamble
has been muddying the water. The rate of technological obsolescence in that
business is certainly higher than that for bread and butter.
Food manufacturers retain some defensive charms, given that the sector
yields close to 4 per cent. They also account for five of the 10
highest-yielding stocks in the FT-SE 350, while the last time any one of
them cut their dividend was back in 1978. Still, dividends have to be paid
out of earnings at the end of the day. Food manufacturers must show how they
can grow.
</TEXT>
