<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / The Lex Column: Banking on BCI's appeal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
By offering shares in Banca Commerciale Italiana at a 5.3 per cent discount
to the market price, the Italian government is showing growing confidence.
The privatisations of Credito Italiano in December and IMI last month were
both heavily oversubscribed. The rise in Credito's shares since then must
have made some in government wonder whether the 10 per cent discount for
that offer was, in retrospect, too generous.
While Credito's shares stood close to a 12-month low when its offer was
priced, though, BCI has risen by 25 per cent this year to an all-time high.
Credito was trading at a discount to net assets in December, while BCI is
trading at around book value. On that basis BCI is being offered at nothing
like a bargain basement price. Like Credito, BCI's interest margins are
being squeezed by lower short-term interest rates. It faces the similar
challenge of keeping operating expenses under control while developing new
sources of income, primarily by selling financial services through an
expanding branch network. The promise of 20 per cent annual growth in fee
income will be difficult to fulfil.
With lower exposure to celebrated corporate collapses such as Ferruzzi, BCI
arguably has the edge in terms of asset quality. That said, its relatively
low level of provisioning might leave less scope for earnings growth as the
Italian economy turns and the bad debt situation improves. Given the
interest shown in Credito and IMI, it is difficult to believe that BCI will
be anything other than oversubscribed. Neither would it do to count on a
windfall profit.
</TEXT>
