<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Observer: Royal treatment
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
But now for a bank that has at least got something right.
For, in this age of high-powered manipulative image-making, it's a rare
treat indeed to discover a low-key corporate PR tool which has served its
purpose for 75 years, and is still going strong.
The Royal Bank Letter, published six times a year by Royal Bank of Canada,
is more akin to Reader's Digest - without the ads - than a corporate
brochure. It carries the bank's logo but otherwise eschews suggestions of
anything so vulgar as a sales pitch.
Instead, the four-page essays - sent free to readers - deal with such homely
and safe subjects as science in our lives; middle age; strength of
character; and 'the civilised workplace'.
Royal Bank tried to save money in the early 1980s by culling the subscriber
list - to no avail. Circulation has soared from 100,000 to 270,000 in the
past decade. Most newspapers can only look on in wonderment.
</TEXT>
