FT  28 FEB 94 / Observer: Hoarety
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Most high street bank customers can warm to the subject of slipping
standards of service, but it seems that the deep pile carpet at even the
most recherche private bank is also wearing distinctly thin.
C. Hoare &amp; Co's worthy 322-year-old tradition certainly proved cold comfort
to one customer of 35 years' standing who decided to vote with his feet
after being informed, by letter, that the rate on his overdraft would be
soaring to 7 per cent over base.
His account had dipped Pounds 20,000 into the red, a not uncommon
occurrence, and hardly a vast sum considering that the bank held
title deeds to his house as well as sundry life policies with a combined
worth well over Pounds 1m. He admits he had moved his securities portfolio,
over which the bank used to have a charge, to his stockbroker for ease of
administration, but that had been nearly 12 months previously.
To add insult to injury, that discreet personal service for which he had
long paid so dearly ran to a distant 'Dear Sir' atop the offending missive.
