<PROFILE>_AN-EB1DPACLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / 'Austrian' recipe for prosperity: For an antidote to
American economic correctness, Michael Prowse examines an intriguing
counter-culture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you want to be 'economically correct', order this year's Economic Report
of the President. You will learn from President Clinton's Council of
Economic Advisers that increases in tax rates need not undermine economic
incentives, that numerical targets for imports can be preferable to free
trade, and that government intervention is often necessary to correct
'market failures'.
This casual rejection of free market orthodoxy will not raise eyebrows in
most US or British universities. In academia, the influence of Milton
Friedman and other members of the 'Chicago School' has been on the wane for
nearly a decade. Even before Mr Clinton's election victory, the most
influential school in the US was the neo-Keynesian, technocratic brand of
economics taught at universities such as Harvard and the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
Yet the range of economic opinion in the US is still encouragingly wide.
There are many able - if unsung - American economists who reject both
neo-Keynesian orthodoxy and crude free market monetarism. 'Austrian'
followers of F A Hayek and Ludwig von Mises constitute one of the most
intriguing counter-cultures.
The 'Austrian school' was founded in the 1870s by Carl Menger, the great
19th-century economist. But it long ago slipped its Viennese moorings.
Today, most German-speaking economists regard themselves as part of the
Anglo-American economic mainstream. Austrians have a niche position in the
US largely due to the efforts of Mises, who was driven to New York in 1940
by the rise of Nazism. Mises was the undisputed leader of the Austrian
school during the interwar years; young Hayek one of his star pupils.
During the 1950s and 1960s, Mises attracted a new band of American
disciples, the most important being Israel Kirzner, who heads a team of
Austrian theorists at New York University, and Murray Rothbard, now at the
University of Nevada. There are centres of Austrian research scattered
across the US, for example at the Mises Institute in Alabama, at George
Mason University near Washington DC and at Hillsdale College in Michigan.
Austrian economists are spread thinly. But they pop up in surprising places.
There are sympathisers at the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas and, perhaps,
even at the Fed's headquarters in Washington: Mr Alan Greenspan's speeches
occasionally have an Austrian tinge. In Britain leading Austrians include
Stephen Littlechild, the regulator of the power industry.
Before looking at Austrian theories, a word of warning is appropriate.
Austrians pride themselves on their realism: they seek to analyse market
capitalism as it is, not as it might be. As a result, the novelty of their
approach is not always obvious to lay people. The real significance of
Austrian economics can be grasped only by contrasting it with the
'mainstream' economics taught in most universities. Believe it or not, the
latter is often only tenuously related to real-world business.
In recent decades, mainstream economists - in common with other social
scientists - have tried to gain respectability by acquiring the trappings of
a 'hard' science, such as physics. We are all familiar with the huge
computer models used to generate those comically inaccurate economic
'forecasts'. But, in truth, maths is now central to every aspect of academic
economics.
Human beings are treated as though they were robot calculators, forever
maximising profits or 'utility' subject to known (or at least precisely
quantifiable) constraints. Prices are assumed to move rapidly to bring
supply and demand into balance so that markets are always at or close to
'equilibrium'. The upshot is that all the complexities and uncertainties of
a market economy are reduced to a series of neat equations.
This makes economics look more sophisticated than in the days of Adam Smith
(or even John Maynard Keynes). But is the pretension to scientific
understanding justified? Can the kind of maths used to describe the natural
world really be brought to bear on the decisions of human beings? Is
economics really this tractable?
Austrians think not. In real science, there are plenty of 'constants' -
precise relationships confirmed by numerous experiments. After decades of
effort, Rothbard points out, economists have not come up with a single
'economic constant'. All they can ever say is that certain relationships
held at certain times in certain places. The crucial difference is that
human beings can (and frequently do) alter their behaviour - an option not
open to planets or atoms.
Eschewing higher maths, modern Austrians, such as Kirzner, advocate an
alternative economic paradigm that lays greater stress on the role of
entrepreneurs as the driving force of capitalism and on markets as dynamic
processes that facilitate innovation and discovery. To put it bluntly,
Kirzner creates room for such real-world phenomena as Rupert Murdoch, the
Australian media tycoon. By contrast, the insipid world of mainstream
economics could be populated entirely by intelligent computers. The
difference between Austrian and mainstream economics is the difference
between a creative art and a dull, predictable science.
Kirzner follows Mises in putting entrepreneurs at the centre of economic
action. Mises (see Human Action, Yale University Press, 1949) was always
unhappy with the conventional model of economic man as a kind of 'robot
maximiser'. He felt it was simply incorrect to depict most economic
decisions as a matter of routine optimisation subject to known constraints.
He realised that business is a creative activity involving inspired hunches
and leaps of faith.
According to Mises, all you can assume is that people, facing a radically
uncertain future, try to improve their material lot. They act purposefully
to 'remove felt uneasiness'. But Misesian 'human action' does not assume
anybody will optimise anything: he thus dispenses with most of the complex
maths that clutters modern textbooks.
'We are all entrepreneurs,' was one of Mises's favourite slogans. What he
meant was that all economic activity is inherently entrepreneurial because
it occurs in conditions of uncertainty. When we buy a house or choose a
career we have to take a gamble. We have to make assumptions about future
real estate prices or wages that may or may not be justified. If we guess
correctly we prosper, but there is always a risk of disappointment.
Mises saw all economics in this light. Business tycoons are really no
different from you or me. They gamble that the price at which they can sell
a product tomorrow will more than offset the cost today of the labour and
raw materials needed to produce it. If they are correct, they make big
profits; if they are wrong they face bankruptcy. Whatever happens, they must
remain alert because rivals are always scavenging for profits.
The Austrian concept of markets as dynamic processes is equally fundamental.
Mises had no patience with the traditional emphasis on 'equilibrium states'
which assumes that prices adjust swiftly to bring demand and supply into
perfect balance. In the real world, he pointed out, the conditions for
equilibrium were constantly changing; the mix of products towards which
business was striving today would be redundant tomorrow because of changes
in consumer tastes, business technology, government policy and a host of
other factors.
Equilibrium was thus like the crock of gold at the end of the rainbow. It
was something you might approach but could never attain. 'Perfect
competition' was not, as the textbooks implied, a characteristic of an
equilibrium state in which myriads of identical companies passively accepted
prices set by the market. It was, rather, a messy process in which,
typically, a few big companies battled for supremacy and enjoyed
considerable pricing power. It was a disequilibrium process that defied
mathematical analysis.
This may seem an abstruse point. Who cares if markets are in equilibrium or
not? But it turns out to be of crucial importance because the criteria by
which mainstream economists judge economic efficiency relate to equilibrium
situations. When Mr Clinton's advisers talk about 'market failure', they are
referring to the failure of real-world economies to achieve the efficiency
conditions implied by their imaginary equilibrium models.
Austrian analysis sweeps these concerns aside. Since real-world economies
are never in equilibrium, the efficiency conditions never apply. There is no
such thing as 'market failure' in the sense intended by Harvard-types
because the criteria for market success - the mathematical efficiency
conditions - apply only in non-existent situations.
Since Austrians do not believe you can prove free markets are efficient, why
are many deeply opposed to government intervention? Hayek provided the most
convincing answer. In the 1940s, he stressed a seemingly obvious but
hitherto ignored fact: the sum total of knowledge available in an economy
'never exists in concentrated or integrated form but solely as the dispersed
bits of incomplete and frequently contradictory knowledge which all the
separate individuals possess'.
What Hayek meant is that you and I (and the managers of private-sector
companies) know far more about our circumstances and desires than could ever
be acquired by a central authority. Even if governments could obtain and
process all the information dispersed throughout a market economy (an
impossible task), they would still not know enough to make the 'right'
decisions. This is because we often do not know in advance what knowledge
will be relevant to our decisions: we thus could not keep government
officials fully informed even if this were our goal.
Mainstream economists still talk grandly about 'maximising social welfare'.
Hayek's point about the dispersal of knowledge shows that this goal is
really nonsensical. Nobody could know enough to measure society's welfare,
let alone to maximise it.
Hayek's central point is not that market prices convey and summarise
already-existing knowledge - something most economists would accept. It is,
rather, that the incentives offered by market prices during the dynamic
process of competition lead to the discovery and dissemination of new
knowledge. As Kirzner stresses, they promote innovation and growth by
'alerting hitherto unwitting market participants to the possibility of pure
entrepreneurial profit . . .' Such discoveries, argues Kirzner, 'constitute
the crucial steps through which markets tend to achieve . . . successively
better co-ordinated states of society'.
Austrians believe decentralised markets will nearly always outperform
bureaucrats for two reasons. They provide access to far more of the relevant
information (in terms both of personal preferences and technological
options) and they provide strong incentives (in the shape of profit
opportunities) for using the information efficiently. Even if governments
can somehow discover what to do, officials typically lack appropriate
incentives: remuneration, for example, is rarely linked to the economic
performance of sectors they regulate or control.
The principal task of government should thus be to eliminate obstacles that
prevent markets operating smoothly. Since markets are in continual flux,
Austrians do not regard any particular market structure as ideal. In some
sectors peak efficiency may be achieved through competition between only a
handful of large enterprises; in others it may require hundreds or thousands
of competitors. The efficient number and size of companies, moreover, will
change over time.
The crucial requirement is that individuals and companies (foreign as well
as domestic) always be allowed to enter existing markets and compete away
the profits of established companies. With completely free entry, Austrians'
claim, entrepreneurial competition becomes an upward spiral leading to ever
higher standards of living.
Government regulation is no substitute for more intense competition because
it tends to stifle the innovation that leads to economic growth; indeed
Austrians such as Kirzner argue that the true cost of intervention, while
high, is impossible to calculate because nobody can predict what advances
would occur in its absence.
Austrian theories will appear realistic or naive depending upon one's
temperament and experience. But in forming a judgment, bear in mind that
Austrians have an excellent track record on the central economic debate of
this century. Mises published the first coherent critique of socialist
economics as early as 1920. During the 1930s, he and Hayek stood virtually
alone against the economics profession in arguing that central planning
could not work. The technocrats who saw economics as akin to engineering (a
science independent of politics) were still defending socialism in the
mid-1980s. They still run the profession but somewhere up there, Mises is
having the last laugh.
</TEXT>
