<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: Malta full prepared for admission
into European Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr STEPHEN C CALLEYA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The FT survey on Malta (February 18) provides a very accurate synopsis
of Malta's proactive domestic and foreign policy agenda for the 1990s. I
would, however, like to raise two points of clarification with particular
reference to Robert Graham's assessment of Malta's EU application.
First, the Fenech Adami administration has consistently declared that Malta
is fully committed to subscribing to the EU's common and foreign security
policy (CFSP).
In fact, there is no need for any constitutional amendments prior to EU
accession because Malta's neutrality, which is based on the principles of
non-alignment, in no way contradicts what is stated in Title V of the
Maastricht treaty.
A specific section of the title stipulates that the introduction of a CFSP
does not mean that member states cannot continue making their own specific
security arrangement: 'The policy of the Union in accordance with this
Article (Article J4) shall not prejudice the specific character of the
security and defence policy of certain Member States.'
In addition, admission of the neutral European Free Trade Association
countries will establish the framework to accommodate the Maltes whose
neutrality is 'sui generis'.
Second, if the institutional implications of the four EFTA candidates do not
present a problem for the EU decision-making process, it is difficult to
comprehend how the case of Malta will. To suggest that EU institutional
reform should be a prerequisite to the vetting of Malta's application would
be setting a precedent and equivalent to re-writing EC history itself.
Moreover, the ministry of foreign affairs is already in the process of
building a professional diplomatic corps that will be adequately prepared to
assume the administrative and bureaucratic responsibilities that EU
membership will entail.
Stephen C Calleya,
department of politics and international studies,
University of Warwick,
Coventry CV4 7AL
</TEXT>
