<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: R&amp;D systematically undervalued in UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ROGER LYONS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The question of reporting R&amp;D expenditure is not just an issue for
accounting standards ('Companies breach R&amp;D accounting standards', February
24). MSF, the largest union for scientists and technologists in the private
sector, believes the contribution of R&amp;D expenditure to the future wealth of
the UK is being systematically undervalued.
At present there is no requirement for companies to report properly defined
R&amp;D expenditure in their company accounts and reports.
According to a 1993 study by Company Reporting, of the 43 per cent of
companies that reported R&amp;D expenditure in their annual reports, 25 per cent
gave no further details in their accounts. Is it no wonder that this creates
an image among brokers that R&amp;D expenditure is not important? The government
and both sides of industry must promote the importance of R&amp;D expenditure.
MSF has long argued that this debate could properly be stimulated by
introducing legislation to make reporting of properly defined R&amp;D
expenditure compulsory.
However, we suspect that the government would oppose any such move as 'red
tape' and over-regulation of industry, even though this would send a message
to investors, customers and employees alike, about a company's commitment to
product development.
Roger Lyons,
general secretary,
MSF,
Park House,
64-66 Wandsworth Common,
North Side,
London SW18 2SH
</TEXT>
