<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / People: 'Classic HR requirements' at SCA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
New Zealand is about as far away as you can get from Sweden, but it is to
New Zealander Larry Simpson that the big Swedish pulp and paper group SCA
has turned to make the highly unusual appointment of a foreigner to be group
human resources director, writes Hugh Carnegy.
Simpson, currently in charge of human resources in Europe and Africa for
DHL, will leave his present base in Brussels later next month for Stockholm
where, according to SCA information chief Sten Lindholm, he will be unique
as a non-native personnel director in a big Swedish corporation.
SCA counts one other foreigner - Briton Colin Williams - among the ranks of
its top nine executives. He heads SCA Packaging, but is based in Brussels.
Lindholm says SCA is looking to Simpson to bring a breadth of vision to the
management of human resources in the group, which has been undergoing
significant restructuring.
Simpson, 45, took his time saying yes to the job. He was first approached a
year ago. But he says he is 'very impressed' by the quality of his new
Swedish colleagues - and attracted by life in the somewhat staid but
beautiful city of Stockholm.
'Sixty five per cent of SCA's business is derived from outside Sweden so it
is logical for them to have a mix of people at the top - to have a broad
view and not just a Swedish view,' he says. He perceives some 'classic HR
requirements' at SCA, including the development of senior management,
recruitment, mobility of staff and pension and cost issues.
Simpson has worked for 13 years for DHL, first in New Zealand, then in
Singapore, before moving to Europe. He is looking forward to enjoying
Sweden's ample opportunities for skiing and sailing. But his first priority
is to learn Swedish - even if that is unlikely to be a real requirement in
Stockholm where even most taxi drivers seem fluent in English.
</TEXT>
