<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Management: Untangled web reaps its reward - Why Coats took
top prize for its published accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'You have to be comfortable in exposing yourself,' says Neville Bain, chief
executive of UK-based textiles group Coats Viyella, with just a touch of
smugness.
Only a few years ago, the idea of Coats reaching the shortlist for, let
alone winning, the annual Stock Exchange and Chartered Accountants award for
published accounts would have been unthinkable. The company was more
notorious for concealing information than revealing it.
So for New Zealand-born Bain, and finance director Russell Walls - both
appointed to their current positions in 1990 - the recent award is
especially sweet.
Bain's claim to have banished secrecy and opacity - barely a page in the
winning report is free of reference to disclosure - will not necessarily
convince the City sceptics.
Helen James, textiles analyst at James Capel, remarks: 'It's sycophantic in
the extreme. I'm not surprised they won after they put all that goody-goody
rubbish in it.' But she also gives credit where it is due. 'There used to be
about 200 reporting divisions so no one knew what was going on,' she says.
The Coats conversion to Cadbury principles of corporate governance,
environmental reporting and early adoption of the Accounting Standards
Boards changes on financial statements - some of the items that caught the
judges' eyes - has been a gradual process, even under the muscular new
management team.
The 1989 and 1990 reports, for example, were long on glossy photographs but
still short on disclosure. In 1991, things began to look brighter. Bain had
taken on a design consultancy, Merchant Corporate Design, and a slogan: 'The
Colourful World of Coats Viyella'. Divisional reporting was clearer - much
needed, given the spread over six business streams from fashion retail to
precision engineering - and the company's executive structure was better
explained.
The most important innovation was a comprehensive financial review, partly
to address speculation about the goodwill and fair value adjustments that
accompanied Coats' successful contested bid for Tootal that year.
The award-winning 1992 report built on these improvements and went a stage
further.
'Our brief from Neville Bain was to produce a structured document that
showed exactly how the divisions contributed to the whole, that showed the
company was keen on disclosure, and a new emphasis on the importance of
design and customer service,' says Catherine Samy, managing director of
Merchant.
Pages of advertisement-style photographs, accompanied by short texts, are
designed to highlight aspects of Coats' closeness to the customer. The
divisional reporting is crisper, and the financial review is clear and
detailed.
Richard Sykes QC and his panel appear to have been most impressed by Coats'
obvious desire to conform with accounting best practice. Sykes warmly
praised the 'full notes' on the introduction of the 1992 accounting standard
FRS3 and the early adoption of FRED3, both of which affect the presentation
of the results of UK companies.
'Coats Viyella's accounting change is to be applauded,' he said. Corporate
governance had been 'dealt with very well' - with a full statement on the
Cadbury report - as had the company's section on environmental policy.
As Coats plunges into the production of its 1993 report - the report team
does not write any 'filler' text before the figures are in - one question
remains. Did Coats win because it has gone in four short years from being
one of the most uninformative on the Stock Exchange to a model of disclosure
 -or because it was simply the best?
'The report is very, very detailed,' says James. 'They have improved their
presentation dramatically. But they are not particularly ahead of anybody
else.'
So one suspects that Coats' report is being rewarded for two things: most
improved performance on disclosure, and a gorgeous cover.
</TEXT>
