<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Management: Making more of research
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How does the UK get better value out of its burgeoning management research
industry? The country now has more than 100 business schools - roughly half
of whose 4,100 academics are thought to be active in research - yet it is
widely agreed that their quality and impact is variable.
Such a feeling prompted the Economic &amp; Social Research Council in late 1992
to look at the issues under the aegis of a commission chaired by Professor
George Bain of the London Business School.
Many of the recommendations of its final report* published this month are
concerned with sustaining and improving the quality of research. But there
is also strong emphasis on improving its relevance to users - managers,
entrepreneurs, policymakers, consultants and trade unions, for example -
notably in the proposal for an independent management research forum to
generate debate about priorities.
The forum as outlined could have other roles, including helping to increase
the exchange of knowledge between academic and user communities and helping
to develop research partnerships. Researchers are also urged to support
their proposals to the ESRC with 'user strategies'.
The report argues for increased public funding but says this should be
matched with co-funding from institutions and business. It states that 'good
management research develops from a synergy between the needs of practising
managers and the inquisitive, analytical, explanatory approach adopted by
academics. And the best management research lifts itself above immediate
problem-solving to provide perspectives that contribute towards a cumulative
understanding of management and the environments in which it operates'.
*The Research Evaluation Division, Economic &amp; Social Research Council. Tel:
0793 413010. Fax: 0793 413001.
</TEXT>
