<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / The Business Traveller: How to tackle the touts - What can
you expect when you step off the aircraft in Latin America? Stephen Fidler
guides you to the hotel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As Latin America opens up its markets and enjoys an investment boom, more
and more foreign business travellers are heading south. They are discovering
that the spirit of commerce is thriving in airports all over the region:
local 'entrepreneurs' offer to carry suitcases, ferry them to their hotels,
or provide other services.
Particularly for the traveller who does not speak the local language, it can
be a stressful experience. It can be even more disorientating in the
northern winter, when the heavily clad voyager exits into the tropical heat
of the southern summer.
The good news is that, in most of the region, immigration and customs
facilities have much improved in recent years. Land crossings may be
different, but the airports in most Latin American capitals are not too
difficult to cope with. In most places, you can forget about the caricature
of a soldier picking through your belongings and awaiting a bribe.
Most countries now have red or green customs channels. Others operate a
system of random customs checks: travellers press a button, which shows
green, for go, or red, at which point you are directed to a desk to answer a
few questions and have your luggage looked at.
There are exceptions, but most customs officers do not appear to be too
worried about visiting foreign business people. There can still be awkward
moments, in both passport and customs areas. Some business people say you
are less likely to be bothered by customs if you go to Venezuela on a
tourist rather than a business visa, for example. Having several computers
with you might attract the attention of customs officers in Brazil.
But it is outside the customs hall that the main action starts. Of all the
most common business destinations in Latin America, the airport where you
are most likely to be hassled is Caracas. It is usually hot and sticky,
overcrowded and full of locals eager to help with your luggage.
In addition, the system of booking an official taxi at most Latin American
airports - where you buy a ticket at a booth - seems not to work in Caracas.
The booth is there, right next to the bureau de change on the way out, but
it usually proves impossible to communicate - in any language - with the
people behind the counter. They nod their head or point their lips - this
latter gesture is a Venezuelan peculiarity - in the direction of the touts
you have been fending off for the last five minutes.
When you get outside, you will probably find a 1970s American gas-guzzling
car - petrol is still only 5 US cents a litre in Venezuela - to transport
you to the hotel. It is best to fix a price beforehand, if you can.
Venezuelans pay about Dollars 18; visitors should pay no more than Dollars
25. Drivers may try to charge multiples of that to business people
travelling in twos or threes. Don't let them. Be ready, if you arrive during
the day, to put up with the miserable traffic jams.
If your reception at Caracas airport seems overenthusiastic, it tends to be
the opposite in Bogota, where visitors sometimes have to roam the airport
looking for a taxi. Once I succumbed to the entreaties of the owners of an
unmarked vintage Lada, of whom I was deeply suspicious but who turned out to
be charming and drove me to the hotel for a pittance.
Taxi drivers in the Colombian capital are all said to carry guns, so I have
resolved not to argue with them too vigorously. This can be tough: on one
occasion, my cab drove into the side of another taxi at a crossroads and,
when I got out, the driver demanded the fare - even though I was still a
long way from my destination. I paid.
Lima worries some travellers - one US immigration official in Miami (in
Miami, mark you) once told me I was going to the 'most dangerous place in
the world'. Now the threat of terrorism has receded (not disappeared), the
Peruvian capital's airport, though in a perpetual state of reconstruction,
is not too much of a hassle. If a taxi is not available, many hotels run
buses to and from the airport.
Santiago, now overcrowded but soon to open a brand new terminal building,
Buenos Aires and Montevideo offer few perils to most travellers. In Mexico
City and both of Brazil's main entry points, Sao Paulo and Rio de Janeiro,
it is a good idea to seek out the taxi booths. In Mexico City one is located
just outside the terminal building, while in Brazil the booths of competing
taxi companies are indoors. The taxis are clean and safe, the drivers know
roughly where they are going, and you can usually pay in local or US
currency.
Latin America is not like Switzerland: not even in Costa Rica and Uruguay,
the self-styled 'Switzerlands' of Central and South America. The best way
for the visitor to reduce airport stress is not to fight the local ambience
but to enjoy it.
While airport entrepreneurs certainly want your money, most prefer to obtain
it legally.
</TEXT>
<XX>
