<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Can Europe Compete?: A crossroad of frustrations - Case
Study: unemployment on the German-Polish border
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As pedestrians cross the iron bridge spanning the Oder between Germany and
Poland, a one-legged Polish man brandishes a placard requesting D-Marks to
help him purchase a prosthesis.
Since German unification, the river has become a border not just between
hard and soft currency areas, but between compartments of the European
labour market. Poles and Germans are each having to adjust to the employment
crisis. They are doing so in different ways.
Before 1989-90, 600 Polish women were bused across every day for shift work
in the big semiconductor plant in Frankfurt an der Oder on the western side.
Previously an East German electronic showpiece, the plant once employed
7,100. Since the post-unity industrial downturn, the number has fallen to
400. And the buses have stopped coming.
Officially, unemployment in the Frankfurt region is 16.3 per cent, although
the true figure - taking account of temporary government work and training
schemes - is more than 20 per cent. With employment scarce, a panoply of
rules now keeps Polish workers away from east German jobs.
'The Poles are willing to work for much less money,' says Mrs Eva Novicka,
proprietress of a travel agency in Slubice on the eastern side of the river.
'No German will work for less than DM10 per hour. They are too proud. Poles
will accept jobs for DM7 to DM8.' High east German wages, leading to east
German unit labour costs that are 80 per cent above west German levels, have
lengthened local dole queues. None the less, the D-Mark attracts Poles
across the bridge to seek work in the most unpropitious conditions.
The current earnings gap is huge. This means Poles who carry out illegal
casual jobs at less than half normal German wages still earn much more than
they would in Poland. In the Slubice region, wages can be as low as DM150 to
DM200 a month, says Mr Wilfried Grieger, an official at the Frankfurt
employment office. This compares with DM1,500 to DM2,500 in Germany.
Mr Grieger says the system of work permits for Polish workers rules out
undercutting of official German wages. Also, Poles may work in Germany only
if they fill vacancies for which no German or EU citizens apply. But it is
an open secret that, on east German building sites, contractors pay casual
Polish labourers as little as DM2 an hour, against a German rate of DM15.
Officially, only 373 Polish workers now make the daily cross-border journey
in the Frankfurt area. 'Since there is a black market, the real figure could
be a lot higher. It is impossible to say how high,' says Mr Grieger.
Frankfurt has long been a crossroad of trade routes. But now, it is more a
crossroad of frustrated hopes.
This is part three of a ten-part series. Previous articles appeared last
Thursday and Friday. Tomorrow: Services
</TEXT>
<XX>
