<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Can Europe Compete?: The high price of social cohesion -
Could lower wages for the unskilled speed job creation in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Europe's labour market stands accused. The high cost and low flexibility of
European workers have, it is alleged, seriously impaired the competitiveness
of European business.
The charge sheet boils down to two propositions: imports from low-wage
developing countries are undercutting the products of high-wage European
manufacturers of medium and low-tech goods; while inflexibility and failures
in training and education systems are leaving European countries
ill-equipped to keep abreast of America and Japan in future high-tech
products.
The consequences, the argument goes, have been slow employment growth and
rising wage inequality, alongside high and persistent unemployment. The
underlying fear is European companies will be able to compete in
increasingly competitive world markets only by shedding more and more
labour, compounding unemployment, or by forcing down European wages and thus
living standards.
There is some truth in these charges. But some of these trends affect the
labour markets of all advanced economies. Barriers to global trade, for
example, are continuing to fall for everyone as the technologically
sophisticated workforce of the world grows rapidly. There are now no more
than 600m literate workers in the world able to operate complex
manufacturing equipment, but in the next 20 years the figure could rise to
more than 3bn. World adult literacy, says the United Nations, has increased
from 15 per cent in 1953 to more than 60 per cent.
The effects of this trend, however, can be exaggerated. So far at least,
developing country trade is too small to have significant negative effects
on wages and employment in developed countries - the formers' exports
account for only 3.1 per cent of total manufacturing consumption in
developed countries. Only 5 per cent of EU industrial workers are employed
in sectors which export more than 40 per cent of their output, and only 7
per cent of European GDP is accounted for by imports.
Trade penetration will undoubtedly grow. But, for all advanced economies,
more important in undermining the employment of the unskilled is the shift
towards more sophisticated technology, leading to the employment in
manufacturing of fewer, better educated workers.
What matters for the competitiveness of European business and living
standards is the speed and ease with which wage-setting behaviour and worker
flexibility allow European companies to adjust to changing technology and
international competition.
Europe's recent record does not inspire confidence in its capacity to
change. Over the past 20 years Europe has had higher unemployment and lower
private sector job creation than the US and Japan and a poorer record at
adapting to external shocks, such as the oil price rises.
Labour costs are, on average, higher than in most other parts of the world,
though average hourly wage costs are now below Japan (in USDollars terms).
Moreover, European wage costs increased by 4 per cent per year in the 1980s
against no increase in America and very little in Japan.
But the picture is not overwhelmingly gloomy. European labour productivity
(output per person-hour) has been rising at 2 per cent a year since 1979 in
the economy as a whole. This is slower than Japan's but way ahead of the US
where employment creation in the service sector has held productivity growth
to  1/2 per cent. In manufacturing, Europe has at least kept pace with the
US.
Also, in the sophisticated goods that dominate world trade, labour costs can
be small. In the UK computer industry, for example, wage costs are only 15
per cent of production costs. And the recent trend has been towards wage
restraint in Europe. In Italy the scala mobile, which linked wages to
prices, has ended and even Germany is trimming fringe benefits.
Companies, especially those in high value-added sectors, often say labour
costs are not high on the list of factors affecting European
competitiveness. A private report on jobs and competitiveness by a group of
mainly US multinationals for the European Commission says companies
manufacture in Europe to be close to markets. Job cuts, it adds, are coming
from technical advances and organisational change, not primarily because of
low-cost competition.
Companies opening plants in Asia are doing so for the same reason US
multinationals want to be in Europe - to be close to markets. US computer
giant IBM even says the move into eastern Europe and Asia will create
managerial and logistical jobs in western Europe, at least short-term.
What the companies do complain about in Europe is lack of flexibility.
Limitations on working time, restrictions on using temporary and part-time
workers, and inflexible redundancy laws are the main complaints There has
been a general drift towards deregulation in European labour markets over
the past 10 years, but Britain is still far ahead in terms of ease of firing
and lack of regulation on wage setting, employee consultation and working
time.
Now the low-wage southern European economies, such as Spain, are trying to
loosen up. Some have inherited highly protected product markets which have
allowed a jobs-for-life culture, reinforced by the lack of a proper
state-funded unemployment benefit system. In Spain nearly 40 per cent of the
working population are on temporary contracts because of the difficulty of
firing people on standard contracts.
Few Europeans want to emulate the US, where about two-thirds of workers are
subject to instant dismissal. And there is evidence that short job tenure
reduces the likelihood of decent training, while job insecurity reduces
workers' commitment. So a balance is needed between flexibility and secure
employment, at least for high-skill, high-wage workers.
From an employment and a competitiveness point of view the pool of skilled
workers must become as large as possible.
These 'core' workers need sound basic education and the opportunity to
invest and re-invest in relevant workplace skills, if only so as to be able
to take them elsewhere.
Most European countries' record on basic education and training is superior
to the US, and there has been a sharp increase in the numbers staying on at
school in Spain, Italy, France and Britain. But European basic education
compares far less well with Japan, South Korea and Malaysia. And only about
30 per cent of young Europeans go into higher education, against nearly 70
per cent of young Americans.
The problem is that the core will never embrace all workers, and for those
outside that core Europe has provided fewer jobs than the US and Japan. In
those countries there are more jobs of the sort that anyone can do. This is
because their wages are lower and because the wage floor determined by
minimum wages and welfare benefits - about 40 per cent of average incomes in
most European countries - is less generous.
Real wages in Europe have risen in the past decade even for the bottom
decile, while in the US they have fallen sharply for the poorest workers.
That is one reason why between 1970 and 1992, when the US and EC economies
grew by similar percentages, US employment rose 45 per cent and EC
employment only 7 per cent.
Europe thus faces a dilemma: the fall in the real wages of the unskilled,
which the US experience suggests is needed to speed employment creation,
would mean wider income inequality than most governments will tolerate in a
continent claiming to value social cohesion as well as competitiveness.
The challenge is to find ways of supporting low wage households which speed
job creation rather than compound the poverty and unemployment traps which
already exist in many European countries.
</TEXT>
<XX>
