<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Managers see pay increase sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Managerial pay awards rose markedly in the three months to the end of
January, the first upturn in the level of managerial salary increases since
the summer of 1990, Richard Donkin writes.
The March issue of Incomes Data Services' Management Pay Review, which
analysed salary awards in 183 groups of managerial and professional staff,
says median awards rose from 2.5 per cent in the three months to October
1993 to 3 per cent in the latest period.
IDS interprets the rise as an indication of 'broad stability' rather than
recovery. It also says that pay increases are becoming more complex since a
growing number of companies are adopting Inland Revenue approved tax-free
profit-related pay schemes.
Pay figures released by the Engineering Employers' Federation today show
that settlements remain around 2 per cent. The average level of settlement
in member companies from November to January was 2.16 per cent.
</TEXT>
