<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Tunnel's friends dig in 100 feet down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eurotunnel may be late, over budget and widely scorned. But it knows how to
throw a party.
On Saturday it invited 800 people to lunch 100ft below the seabed and 7km
out from the British side. For the occasion a cavernous crossover point of
the tracks became a giant banqueting hall with 100 tables and twinkling
tricolour lights, video screens and a string quartet.
The event, inspired by Brunel's 1827 dinner in his recently completed Thames
Tunnel, was Eurotunnel's way of saying 'thank you' to all the friends who
helped it through the agonies of its eight-year life.
The British guests, who had to be brought in by British Rail because Le
Shuttle is not ready, arrived 90 minutes late but were delighted to find
that they had beaten the French.
Lady Thatcher, the guest of honour and, according to her hosts, the 'main
inspiration' for the project, proclaimed the triumph of private finance.
'Without it, this would never have happened,' she said. 'The paper we signed
to make this possible was worth a lot more than all the other bits of paper
we signed in the second half of this century.' Mr Jacques Delors was not
among those present.
The timing of this grandiose event, with its proclamations of amitie, was
not the best, coming as it did at the end of a week which had seen the
publication of 'Chanteclair's' anti-British diatribe and a further move by
the Paris government to prevent the anglicisation of French.
Eurotunnel's friends evidently do not include members of the British
government, whose dithering over the rail link added to its difficulties.
The most prominent active politician present was Mr John Prescott, shadow
transport secretary. But the Bank of England, the big clearing banks,
merchant banks and stockbrokers were there.
Observer, Page 17
</TEXT>
