<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Public access to Bar urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A barristers' think-tank set up to find ways of ensuring the survival of an
independent Bar in the face of increased competition from solicitors for
advocacy work has recommended that the public should have direct access to
barristers, Robert Rice writes.
At present only solicitors, a limited number of professional clients, such
as accountants, and overseas clients have direct access to the Bar.
A consultation document issued by the Bar's policy unit, chaired by Mr James
Munby QC, says existing restrictions should be abolished. These prevent lay
clients from consulting barristers directly for legal advice unconnected
with a court case.
Clients should also be able to approach a barrister directly in connection
with a court action, but barristers should be under a duty to refer them to
a solicitor as soon as practicable.
The reason for not recommending that the public should be able to instruct
barristers directly in court actions is said to be to allow barristers 'to
continue to concentrate on specialist consultancy and advocacy leaving the
bulk of the work of preparing a case for trial to the solicitor'.
</TEXT>
