<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / IMF demands may delay debtdeal for Brazil
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Citibank, the closing agent for Brazil's rescheduling of its private bank
debt, is ready to extend the deal's notification deadline. This suggests
concern over whether the International Monetary Fund will approve the
country's economic reforms.
The proposed extension comes at a difficult moment for Mr Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, finance minister. He is expected to announce today the next step in
his economic restructuring programme, and is running out of time to close
the bank deal and launch a bid for Brazil's presidency.
Citibank had announced a deadline of March 11 for notification by Brazil
that the exchange of old debt for new would go ahead on April 15, the last
date possible under existing agreements. Brazil needs an IMF accord before
the US Treasury will issue zero-coupon bonds to guarantee part of the
package.
But Citibank is now looking to extend the notification deadline for up to a
week. 'We are studying the possibility of giving notice of the debt exchange
a few days later than March 11,' said Mr William Rhodes, vice-chairman.
An IMF team is in Brazil looking at the reform package announced by Mr
Cardoso. This includes the promise of a balanced budget this year and a
planned new currency. The country is plagued by annual inflation of about
2,500 per cent.
But the IMF is thought to be pushing Brazil to run a budget surplus. It may
also be reluctant to grant Brazil an accord until Mr Cardoso's package is
implemented, especially given the country's record of signing then ignoring
letters of intent with the IMF.
According to a Brazilian banker, Citibank's decision does not mean the
Dollars 52bn (Pounds 35bn) rescheduling is yet threatened, but it does
suggest discussions with the IMF are tense. If the IMF does not sign the
accord, the creditor banks could arrange a further extension, although this
would be difficult for technical and timing reasons. As an alternative,
Brazil could buy the zero-coupon bonds in the market, but this would be
expensive and there may not be enough bonds available.
The extension may frustrate any presidential ambitions of Mr Cardoso.
Brazilian law requires that he resign and declare his candidature by April 2
for the election in October. He is thought to want to run, but only if his
reforms are on course and the bank deal is concluded. After Citibank's
extension, and delays to his economic package, he is running out of time to
act.
Mr Rhodes said the outcome of the IMF's discussions with Brazil should be
'clear within a couple of weeks. I remain optimistic there will be an IMF
letter of intent no later than a month from now and the exchange of
documents on April 15 will go ahead,' he said.
Nancy Dunne adds from Washington: The US has dropped its long-running trade
case against Brazil's patent, trademark and copyright laws, amid praise by
the US trade representative for Brazil's 'continued progress in improving
protection of intellectual property rights' and 'its leadership role through
early implementation of the Uruguay Round intellectual property provisions.'
Ending several days of intense negotiations, as Brazil sought to head off
sanctions, Mr Mickey Kantor, the representative, praised new Brazilian
regulations on technology transfer and increased efforts to enforce
trademark and copyright laws.
Brazil also has promised to introduce amendments to a pending industrial
property law to strengthen protections.
</TEXT>
