<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Algerian pact with IMF soon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Algerian leaders are expected to sign a letter of intent with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in the next few weeks after the visit to
Algiers last week by Mr Michel Camdessus, IMF director-general.
After signing the letter, the government, led by Mr Redha Malek, is expected
to seek a rescheduling of Algeria's debt to sovereign creditors through the
Paris Club. The stage would then be set for France to seek from its European
Union partners a loan to help support Algeria's balance of payments worth
around Dollars 1bn (Pounds 685m)
Two factors have forced the Algerians to reschedule official debt, something
they had long sought to avoid. The more immediate is the sharp decline last
year in the price of hydrocarbons, which will reduce the country's foreign
income by a fifth this year to about Dollars 8bn. Just as important is the
domestic decision, two years ago, to reverse the bold economic reforms
launched in 1989. The IMF and the country's international creditors had
given their imprimatur in June 1991.
Stalling on essential reforms and the weakening price of oil, which accounts
for the bulk of the country's foreign receipts, will in the absence of any
agreement with its international creditors push the cost of servicing
Algeria's foreign debt to Dollars 9bn in 1994, which is more than its
foreign income.
Once Algeria reaches agreement with the IMF on a broad package of reforms,
it can expect a one-year stand-by credit of Dollars 500m and an oil
compensating facility of Dollars 300m. A Paris Club rescheduling of the
principal repayments, due in 1994, of Algeria's Dollars 13.5bn bilateral
debt with OECD governments would release an estimated Dollars 3.75bn.
There is also a growing consensus among Algeria's leading state creditors in
the west for avoiding a cut in the volume of export credits such as often
occurs after Paris Club reschedulings. Algeria was able last year to draw on
Dollars 3bn of export credits from OECD countries. Japan, which has until
recently made public its hostility to rescheduling, now seems more willing
to accept this approach over Algeria.
The Algerian security forces killed Jaffar El Afghani, head of the Islamic
Armed Group (GIA), the most radical islamic group in Algeria, and eight of
his followers in the Algiers suburb of Bouzareah on Saturday night. The
'holy war on Christians, Jews and non-believers', launched a year ago by the
GIA, has cost the lives of dozens of Algerians and 30 foreigners.
The two paramount leaders of the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS), Mr Abassi
Madani and Mr Ali Belhadj, have been moved meanwhile to the comfortable
hunting lodge of Chateau Holden at Douera near Algiers from the prison at
Tizou Ouzou.
</TEXT>
<XX>
