<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / India budget expected to continue reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Manmohan Singh, the Indian finance minister, is expected to set out plans
for further economic reforms in his annual budget speech today.
Import duties, corporate taxes and possibly interest rates are likely to be
reduced to both promote growth and to continue with the economic
liberalisation programme which Mr Singh and Mr PV Narasimha Rao, the prime
minister, launched in mid-1991.
Mr Singh is also expected to announce measures to cut government borrowings,
which have soared so far above the targets that financial ministry officials
fear over-spending by the public sector could yet stifle efforts to
encourage the private-sector-led expansion. The government, in its Economic
Survey published last week, said the fiscal deficit for the year ending
March 1994 would be 'substantially higher' than the target of 4.5 per cent
of GDP.
Supporters of economic liberalisation have been pressing the government to
use the budget to bring the economy back to the top of the political agenda.
They believe much time was wasted last year when ministers' energies were
absorbed by the violence which swept Bombay and other cities.
Mr Tarun Das, general secretary of the Confederation of Indian Industry, the
employers' organisation, said last week: 'This budget must be dramatic, not
wishy-washy. It must contain substantive reforms. By next year it will be
too late because politicians will be taken up with the next general election
(which must be held by 1996).'
Stock market investors, including foreign fund managers who have put more
than Dollars 1bn (Pounds 685m) into Indian equities in the past nine months,
are also betting on a pro-reform budget. Share prices have doubled in the
past year and could fall sharply if the budget proves a disappointment.
The Economic Survey included some general indications of likely reforms. The
report said further reductions in government subsidies for food and other
commodities were necessary to help cut government spending. It urged
ministers to widen the tax net and replace the present complex system of
excise duties levied at varying rates with a simple value-added tax-based
system. It also called for the government to pull further out of the
economy, with more privatisation and an easing of controls on trade, land,
finance and labour.
Labour law reform is a particularly sensitive area because India's laws
severely limit employers' rights to make workers redundant or even to
redeploy them. The Economic Survey said companies could not gear up for
expanding production if they feared they might later be burdened with excess
labour.
</TEXT>
