<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Yeltsin weakened by rebels' amnesty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Boris Yeltsin has emerged weakened and humiliated by the release
of the leaders of last October's bloody parliamentary uprising in a debacle
which says more about his own administration's incompetence than about the
skill of his foes.
Eight men - including Mr Alexander Rutskoi, the former vice-president who
masterminded the uprising and is likely to run for president in 1996 -
walked free from Lefortovo prison on Saturday after a bungled presidential
attempt to block the amnesty. Others freed included General Albert Makashov,
who launched a bloody assault on Moscow's television tower, and Mr Alexander
Barkashov, leader of a blackshirted neo-Nazi militia which marched around
the White House and kept secret hideaways around town.
Their release has prompted popular fears of new bloody confrontations such
as that which cost 140 lives in October and placed Russia on the verge of
civil war. At the very least it sends a message that such violence can be
condoned in future, even if the likes of Mr Victor Anpilov, a hardline
Communist who has vowed to continue pressing for communism's return, may
find the political climate has changed.
Because the bulk of the conservatives in the state duma (lower house of
parliament) have sought to project a respectable non-violent appearance, the
real danger comes from the indirect consequences of new threats, perceived
and real, which may come from Russia's extremists. The release could
strengthen the hand of those who think Russia needs a return to strong
repressive rule. These include members of the president's entourage and Mr
Vladimir Zhirinovsky.
It will also heighten fears of future instability at a time when the economy
needs stability above anything. Mr Rutskoi's freedom in particular will
provide Mr Yeltsin with a constant critic who can say that, strictly
speaking, he is the country's legal president because Mr Yeltsin violated
the constitution last October. Only the rebellion helped balance the
picture, by portraying his opponents as dangerous men ready to stoop to mob
violence. The amnesty now rehabilitates them.
Perhaps most damaging was the evidence the debacle provided of incompetence
in the president's entourage. The organisers of the rebellion, who said they
were only defending the constitution, were released at the very moment the
president's new assistant, Mr Georgy Satarov, was negotiating with the
parliamentary chairman, Mr Ivan Rybkin, on postponing their release.
Legalistic grounds for a postponement were contained in a letter from the
president to Mr Rybkin saying the parliament had in fact pardoned the men
when it only had the constitutional right to amnesty them. The letter to Mr
Rybkin proposed that parliament do some more work on the amnesty before it
could be implemented.
As one former liberal cabinet minister pointed out: 'There are always tricks
which the administration can produce to deal with such situations, except
here it failed to deliver.' The letter containing the relevant 'trick' was
delivered to parliament well after Mr Yuri Baturin, a lawyer who is the
president's national security adviser, first came up with the formula, and
after Mr Yeltsin ignored the amnesty in a state of the nation address.
By Saturday, a deputy to Mr Alexei Kazannik, the prosecutor-general who
resigned because he could not comply with Mr Yeltsin's requests to stop the
amnesty, had already set in motion the process for their release. Mr Baturin
and Mr Sergei Karaganov, a member of the president's advisory council, said
the incompetence was Mr Kazannik's.
Mr Kazannik is to be replaced by Mr Alexei Illyushenko, a presidential aide
involved last summer in launching unsubstantiated corruption allegations
against Mr Rutskoi.
Part of the blame must be shared by the president himself. Mr Yeltsin's
desire to play the statesman devoted to national reconciliation meant that
he failed to focus sufficiently early on the possible consequences of the
amnesty.
</TEXT>
