<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Japan sets its face against further boost to economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's finance minister, Mr Hirohisa Fujii, yesterday dismissed suggestions
that his country should do more to stimulate its economy, saying there were
no further plans to boost domstic demand.
On his return from a weekend meeting of finance ministers from the Group of
Seven leading industrialised countries near Frankfurt, Mr Fujii said: 'We
are not contemplating additional fiscal steps, because the package we just
announced was very large.'
The Japanese delegation insisted that the more than Y15 trillion (Pounds
95bn) package would accelerate reduction of the trade surplus. But other G7
members said Japan had yet to prove its commitment to strengthening demand.
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US Treasury secretary, said: 'What Japan has done is not
sufficient to get the kind of growth in demand that would have a serious
effect on their budget.'
Other finance ministers stressed that dealings between the US and Japan were
amicable, but that no progress was made on their trade dispute.
The ministers also avoided discussion on currency co-operation, agreeing
that exchange rates must not be used to cut Japan's huge trade surplus.
'I expressed concern that any precipitous yen appreciation would undermine
the effects of Japan's efforts to expand domestic demand,' said Mr Fujii
immediately after the meeting, which went out of its way to soothe market
fears of rising interest rates.
Mr Eddie George, Bank of England governor, was puzzled by the recent bond
market shake-out, which he thought was 'possibly an over-correction. . . .
On the evidence we have heard today, a possible repeat of 1987 is
exaggerated,' he added. 'I cannot see any grounds for thinking the stability
we have achieved is at risk.'
Mr Hans Tietmeyer, Bundesbank president, said 'mistaken assessments' had
given rise to fears that US inflation was on the way up. But these concerns
would not last, and markets would soon calm down from their recent
'over-reaction'.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, UK chancellor, said the news from continental Europe was
significantly more encouraging than it had been at previous recent meetings,
with no danger of the recoveries faltering.
However, Mr Bentsen reiterated his call for European countries, in
particular Germany, to lower interest rates more rapidly. 'Given the
progress Europe has made on inflation, we believe the authorities should
take advantage of any opportunities to reduce rates further,' he said.
Mr Theo Waigel, German finance minister and chairman of the G7 meeting,
repeated official forecasts that the German economy was on track for 1.5 per
cent growth this year.
French representatives had said they expected a further growth spurt in the
second half of this year.
</TEXT>
