<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / G7 ties Russian debt to accord with IMF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KRONBERG, GERMANY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Group of Seven industrialised states told the Russian government this
weekend that it must reach an agreement with the International Monetary Fund
on stabilising inflation and the government deficit before any further debt
rescheduling can be negotiated. At the same time, the G7 finance ministers
want to give more help, particularly through the World Bank, to set up a
proper social security system, thus easing the political backlash against
economic reform.
They suggested World Bank funds from the Dollars 3bn (Pounds 2bn) special
privatisation programme could be used to help set up a social safety net,
although the main resources for any such system would have to come from
Russia itself.
The tough line in insisting on prior agreement with the IMF before any new
round of official debt rescheduling in the Paris Club emerged from
Saturday's meeting between the G7 finance ministers and central bank
governors, and a Russian delegation headed by Mr Sergei Dubinin, acting
finance minister.
It will put the new Russian government under severe time pressure to reach a
deal with the IMF on the conditions for the release of a second Dollars
1.5bn tranche of its special transformation facility, and a Dollars 4.1bn
stand-by credit.
The current agreement on rescheduling Dollars 15bn of official debt with the
Paris Club runs out at the end of April, after being extended by four
months.
Mr Alexander Shokhin, Russian economy minister, said after the talks that
the next meeting with the IMF was planned for mid-March, by when fund
officials would have had a chance to assess some basic budget figures
presented to them last week.
The Russian delegation told the G7 that they intended to reduce inflation in
Russia to a monthly rate of 7-9 per cent by the end of 1994, compared with
22 per cent at the end of 1993. Their planned budget deficit would be
brought down to 5 per cent of gross domestic product.
They also gave 'clear and formal assurances' that the new government
remained committed to the reform programme launched by the previous
administration, headed by Mr Yegor Gaidar.
The G7 ministers were clearly keen to give strong political support to the
reform process, and expressed some reassurance over those commitments. But
many remained profoundly sceptical about the Russian government's ability to
meet its targets. That is why they are insisting so firmly on an early IMF
agreement.
'We are still insisting on full respect for IMF conditionality,' Mr Henning
Christophersen, vice-president of the European Commission, said after the
meeting. 'We cannot have a situation where Russia is treated differently
from everybody else.'
The main way in which the G7 wants to express its political support is in
the drive to provide greater assistance in creating a proper social security
system. At the moment all Russian social assistance is provided in effect
from enterprises and factories, which may be sold off or closed down under
the privatisation programme.
</TEXT>
