<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Romanian unions call 2m on strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUCHAREST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
More than 2m Romanians, a fifth of the workforce, are due to take part in a
general strike today in what is expected to be the biggest show of union
strength since the end of Communist rule in 1989.
Alfa Cartel and CNSLR-Fratia, the two main union blocs, decided to go ahead
with the strike after President Ion Iliescu failed to resolve the conflict
and after inconclusive talks with the government.
The two union blocs are demanding the government implement a collective
labour contract for this year, improve the social security system, and speed
market-led reform.
The weak left-wing minority government has tried to head off the strikes but
the unions last week said its offer to negotiate would not be credible until
it had finished drafting its 1994 budget.
They have also criticised the government for not moving quickly enough to
implement a reform package agreed in December with the International
Monetary Fund. The delay is holding up IMF approval for a new stand-by
arrangement which would unlock Dollars 700m (Pounds 480m) in loans.
The unions say that, for the first time since 1989, 'the whole country will
feel the strike'. They plan to block roads and fuel deliveries, cut bread
production, interrupt telecommunications and shut down most of industry.
The mounting labour unrest has increased pressure on the governing Party of
Social Democracy in Romania to create a new pro-reform coalition. The PSDR
has given itself until tomorrow to complete negotiations on a new coalition
with hardline nationalist and former Communist parties, its allies in
parliament.
But the unions are refusing to support any such coalition and their tough
stance, as well as pressure from abroad, has also pushed the PSDR into
holding talks with pro-reform opposition parties.
</TEXT>
