<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / Pensions switch may have cost taxpayers Pounds 1.3bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK life insurance industry may have earned Pounds 400m to Pounds 1.3bn
of taxpayers' money since 1988 by selling personal pensions, according to an
analysis of government statistics.
The figures also show that about 60 per cent of nearly 5m people who have
taken out personal pensions since 1988 are making no provision for
retirement other than the tax refund paid by the government after they opted
out of state pensions.
The analysis, by the Financial Times in consultation with actuaries, shows
that in the past five years the government has paid about Pounds 10.5bn to
people taking out personal pensions, in the form of rebates on national
insurance contributions. These are paid to encourage people to opt out of
the State Earnings- Related Pension Scheme and into personal pensions.
But insurance industry experts estimate that companies selling personal
pensions typically take 4 per cent to 13 per cent of an individual's tax
rebate in commissions and charges for sales agents and management fees.
Mr Frank Field, MP, chairman of the House of Commons social security select
committee, said it planned to start an inquiry into the transfer of tax
rebates into personal pension plans this April. 'We are going to follow the
pounds and see where they ended up,' he said. 'It is as worrying for the
individuals as it is for taxpayers.'
The figures show that by April 1992 more than 300,000 of the men and women
who contracted out of Serps through a personal pension were going to receive
lower benefits on retirement than if they had remained contracted in. That
is because the rebate system gives far more than a young person needs to buy
pension benefits equivalent to Serps, but far less than an older person
would need.
Department of Social Security and Inland Revenue data show that of the 4.7m
people with personal pensions in April 1992, only 40 per cent are saving
more towards retirement than the rebate itself. But DSS officials were
privately encouraged by recent figures showing an improvement on the 1989-90
tax year. Then, fewer than a third of personal pension holders made extra
contributions.
The rebate is paid to a personal pension account set up with an insurance
company in the individual's name. Low earners pay proportionately more of
their rebates to the insurers.
Mr David Dow, a partner at Wyatt Financial Services, which analyses life
insurers' fees, said: 'On a state contribution of Pounds 700 to Pounds 800 a
year, the impact of a Pounds 2-a-month charge is small. But if you only get
Pounds 200 per year, then the effect is quite great.'
Pensions time bomb: special reports, Page 8
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
