<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 94 / PLO set to reject peace talks: Palestinians dismiss Israeli
plans to restrain Jewish extremists as 'hollow'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON and DAVID HOROVITZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TUNIS, JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Palestine Liberation Organisation is almost certain to refuse a US
invitation to resume peace talks with Israel in Washington this week after
Friday's massacre in Hebron.
PLO officials yesterday brushed aside Israeli government plans to curb
Jewish extremists, describing them as hollow and not a basis for resuming
talks.
'It is too soon,' one official said. 'The blood is still warm.'
Before it agrees to rejoin the talks, the PLO is expected to demand more
extensive measures to disarm Jewish settlers in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip and to protect Palestinians living there.
Another four Palestinians and a Bedouin were killed by Israeli troops and 57
others wounded as violent protests continued over the murder of 43 Moslems
during prayers at a mosque in the West Bank town of Hebron.
The Israeli cabinet instructed the attorney-general to consider outlawing
the racist Kach movement, of which Baruch Goldstein, the American-immigrant
doctor who carried out the Hebron killings, was a member.
The cabinet decided to place five Kach leaders in administrative detention,
disarm about 20, and restrict the movements of a few dozen. One Kach
activist, Shmuel Ben-Ishai, was arrested. 'We've decided to get tough with
the hard core of the extremists,' said Mr Yossi Sarid, environment minister.
Ministers said up to 1,000 Palestinian prisoners would be released in the
next few days.
Mr Yassir Arafat, chairman of the PLO, immediately dismissed the Israeli
moves as 'merely cosmetic', before meeting senior PLO officials at his home
in Tunis.
The Clinton administration said it hoped the Israeli action would induce the
PLO to agree to negotiations in Washington that could change 'realities on
the ground'. But these hopes received a blow when Syria, Jordan and Lebanon
yesterday broke off their peace talks with Israel in the US. The talks had
been due to end on March 2.
In dismissing the Israeli moves, Mr Arafat said: 'We were not expecting
better than this, because the Israeli government did not tackle the issue of
Israeli army involvement, nor provide the basis of international protection
for the Palestinian people, the issues that are very essential for a
successful end of the peace process.'
PLO officials said the meeting was expected to result in demands for tougher
Israeli action and a call for the United Nations Security Council to discuss
protection for Palestinians.
Officials avoided suggesting that Friday's atrocity might lead to an
outright abandonment of further peace talks, but said the issue of the
settlers would have to top the agenda if talks were to resume. 'If the
Palestinian people in the occupied territories do not have sufficient
protection, the entire peace process is immaterial,' added one official.
The Israel cabinet also ordered an official inquiry to establish why Israeli
soldiers failed to block Dr Goldstein's entry into the mosque, why they
failed to stop him firing more than 100 bullets into the rows of kneeling
Palestinian worshippers, and whether soldiers had themselves contributed to
the death toll.
Curfews yesterday failed to deter demonstrators throughout the occupied
territories. In one incident, a Palestinian teenager was killed in Gaza when
soldiers fired into a mosque. Three others died in the West Bank, bringing
the number of Palestinian dead since the massacre to 18.
The violence has also spread to the 800,000-strong Israeli Arab community,
with Jaffa, north of Tel Aviv, the focus of unprecedented clashes throughout
the weekend.
Meanwhile, several hundred people gathered in Jerusalem to pay their last
respects to Dr Goldstein, who was beaten to death after the massacre by
Palestinians inside the mosque.
PLO sets tough terms, Page 6
