<PROFILE>_AN-EB1DPAE0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940226
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 94 / International Company News: New Dollars 1.1bn mutual fund
rescinded by NYSE
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The New York Stock Exchange on Friday suspended trading in the shares of a
new Dollars 1.1bn international mutual fund that was to invest in privatised
companies, and forced the four - day-old share issue to be rescinded, after
the performance of privatised companies' stocks was found to have been
overstated in the fund's prospectus.
The rescinding of such a large stock issue, and the cancellation of all the
trades in the fund's shares that were completed last week, is thought to be
unprecedented.
Between February 18 and February 22, 74.5m shares in The Global
Privatisation Fund, managed by the New York money management group Alliance
Capital, were sold to investors at Dollars 15 each.
However, late last week an analyst at Alliance discovered that the
prospectus for the issue had exaggerated the performance of a composite
index of privatisation stocks.
A chart in the original prospectus had shown that the privatisation index
recorded returns of 170 per cent between the end of 1988 and September 1993,
a performance that compared favourably with several other indices quoted in
the offer document.
In fact, the privatisation index's return over a similar period was 94 per
cent, a poorer return than one of the other indices quoted in the
prospectus, a Morgan Stanley emerging markets index. Alliance Capital said
the mistake was the result of a 'glitch' in the calculations.
Once the error was discovered, the NYSE suspended all trading in the shares.
Alliance Capital, and the Wall Street investment bank leading the
underwriting of the issue, Kidder Peabody, immediately agreed to rescind the
issue and publish a new prospectus with the corrected data.
All trades in the funds shares made over the four days - and the NYSE said
about 4.1m shares had changed hands over the period - were cancelled.
Alliance Capital said that the new offer document would be mailed to
potential investors this week, and it hoped a new pricing date could be set
by Friday.
</TEXT>
